<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Grachev Approves of `Partnership for Peace' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0202180194 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1709 GMT 2 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0202180194 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Russian Defence Minister Pavel Grachev says his 
department on the whole approves of the U.S.-proposed 
Partnership for Peace plan but is opposed to the document being 
used against any third country. 
  If peace is to be maintained, all countries must equally be 
involved, he told Interfax on Wednesday [2 February]. 
  "Although it is a good document politically, said Grachev, 
the Defence Ministry's response to NATO's new plan is rather 
cautious." 
  Grachev is concerned at the fact that all former Warsaw Pact 
nations and the Baltic states were seeing the plan as an 
intermediary stage towards full NATO membership. 
  "If the Partnership for Peace plan will gradually drag those 
states into the North Atlantic Alliance without consent or 
consultations with Russia, we will not support it," he said. 
  In the minister's view, NATO's enlargement poses a certain 
threat to Russian security. 
  Grachev says the PP [Partnership for Peace] plan provides 
for 
coordinated effort by NATO and other countries, Russia included, 
over "an interim period following the break up of the Warsaw 
Pact." Until European political structures emerge, all states 
must cooperate to defuse tensions in the continent, particularly 
in the former Yugoslavia, he said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

