<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   NATO Commander Visits Kantemir Tank Division </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0202182694 Moscow Ostankino Television First Channel 
Network in Russian 1500 GMT 2 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0202182694 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow Ostankino Television First Channel 
Network </F>



<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By correspondents Aleksandr Ostrovskiy and Oleg Nikiforov; </F>
from the "Novosti" newscast] 
  [Text] It is the third day of the visit by 
Lieutenant-General Henning von Ondarza, commander in chief of 
NATO Allied Forces Central Europe, to the central European 
sector. 
  The general has already had a meeting with the chief of the 
Russian Federation General Staff, the commander in chief of the 
land forces, and the command of the Moscow military district and 
paid a visit to the Kantemir Tank Division. 
  Henning von Ondarza was more interested in the soldiers' 
welfare and their attitude to the service as well as in the 
principles underpinning manpower acquisition for subunits than 
in their combat proficiency or modern equipment. 
  The general emphasized that armed forces organizational 
development in Russia and Germany, which are land-based powers, 
is different from that in the United States and the main thing 
is that universal military service obligation should be retained 
in Russia and Germany alike, so that armies do not become closed 
societies and so that high mobilization reserves are preserved. 
  [Begin Von Ondarza, recording in German fading to Russian 
translation] The fact that each person is doing something useful 
for their country is the decisive factor in favor of military 
service obligation. [end recording] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

