<H3> <TI>   Russian, Ukrainian Oblast Leaders Issue Statement </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0202232894 Kiev UNIAN in Ukrainian 2100 GMT 2 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0202232894 </F>
<F P=104>  Kiev UNIAN </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Ukrainian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Donetsk -- At a news conference on 2 February Oblast 
Council Chairman Vadym Chuprun reported on the outcome of the 
meeting of the chairmen of the oblast councils and state 
administrations of 10 Ukrainian and Russian border oblasts, 
which took place in Belgorod on 29 January. Its participants 
considered the draft regulations which will be worked up in two 
weeks and which will determine the principles of mutual 
relations between the neighboring oblasts. 
  According to Vadym Chuprun, the meeting proved that there 
are 
no discrepancies among the leaders of the oblasts, that all 
disputable issues relate mostly to customs service and the 
border, but they should be tackled at the interstate level. At 
the previous meeting of oblast leaders they discussed the issue 
on granting them the status of border zones which would 
contribute to establishing normal mutual relations. This issue 
was to be solved by the governments of both countries. 
Unfortunately, Vadym Chuprun pointed out, while Russia did take 
certain steps in this direction, the Ukrainian Government did 
not respond to the appeal by the participants in the Belgorod 
meeting. The current meeting approved an appeal to Leonid 
Kravchuk and Boris Yeltsin with the request to help establish 
normal neighborly relations between the neighboring states. 

</TEXT>

