<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Adherence to Massandra Accord on Black Sea Fleet Urged </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0202154994 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1137 GMT 2 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0202154994 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Russia believes that the Black Sea Fleet problem 
should be solved immediately on the basis of the relevant 
protocol signed by the Russian and Ukrainian presidents in 
Massandra September 3, 1993. This is stated in a telegram sent 
by Russian Deputy Foreign Minister Sergey Lavrov to the chairman 
of the Sevastopol City Council, Viktor Semyonov, reports the 
newspaper "Slava Sevastopolya." 
  The telegram says that the Russian delegation at the talks 
on 
the Black Sea Fleet is prepared to discuss with the Ukrainian 
delegation, within the shortest possible period, the problems 
associated with the drafting of an understanding, according to 
which the Fleet with its entire infrastructure in Crimea is to 
be used by Russia and fly Russian flags. 
  For its part, the Russian delegation will pay for the part 
of 
the Fleet, including the infrastructure, which in line with 
previous agreements should be part of Ukraine, says the telegram. 
  On Tuesday, in an interview with Interfax, the Ukrainian 
Foreign Minister favored the idea of the Fleet's problem being 
solved on the basis of the Yalta agreements, not the Massandra 
ones. 
  In the summer of 1992, the presidents of Ukraine and Russia, 
Leonid Kravchuk and Boris Yeltsin, signed near Yalta the 
agreement according to which Russia and Ukraine would create 
their Naval forces on the basis of the Black Sea Fleet. During 
their creation, the Fleet would be subordinate to both 
presidents. 
  On September 3, 1993, in Massandra (Black Sea southern 
coast), the two presidents signed agreements according to which 
Ukraine was to hand over to Russia its part of the Fleet as 
repayment of the debt for earlier supplies of Russian energy. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

