<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Officials Reject Revision of Fleet Status </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0202183894 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1507 GMT 2 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0202183894 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "Diplomatic Panorama" feature: by Diplomatic </F>
Correspondents Dmitriy Voskoboynikov, Igor Porshnev, Vitaliy 
Trubetskoy and others] 
  [Text] The Russian Foreign Ministry is not inclined to 
attach too much importance to Ukrainian officials' statements 
advocating a revision of the Massandra agreements on the Black 
Sea Fleet, a high-ranking Russian diplomat told Interfax. 
  He said that these statements must not be taken seriously 
because they were made "in the heat" of the election campaign in 
Crimea. 
  To quote the diplomat, in Massandra the Russian and 
Ukrainian 
presidents agreed that the Black Sea Fleet would be Russian. 
"The talk about changes in Ukraine's official position and about 
a roll- back to the Yalta agreements, according to which the 
Black Sea Fleet was equally divided between Russian and Ukraine, 
might be resumed only if President Kravchuk made a corresponding 
statement," he said. 
  Russia will not depart from the Massandra agreements, a 
high- 
ranking Defense Ministry official told Interfax. 
  He said that the Defense Ministry continued work on new 
agreements that would supplement the Massandra accord. 
  He noted in particular that some of the actions by the 
Ukrainian side contradict with these agreements. "Thus, on 
Wednesday, February 2, the Russian Defense Minister Pavel 
Grachev sent a response to his Ukrainian counterpart Vitaly 
Radetsky in which he opposed Kiev's initiative to institute the 
post of commander of the Sevastopol military district," he said. 
"Why should we institute a separate post if it is already 
occupied by the commander of the Black Sea Fleet, Admiral Eduard 
Baltin, nominated by the presidents of the two countries?" 
  "Suppose we resumed the discussion of the fleet division. 
What then? Even in better times Kiev financed only 16 percent 
of the Black Sea Fleet's needs. Ukraine cannot afford the Black 
Sea Fleet and will auction it off. It is also clear that this 
will not benefit either Russia's or Ukraine's defense 
capability," he said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

