<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Linkage of Problems in Talks Rejected </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  MK0202142094 Moscow NEZAVISIMAYA GAZETA in Russian 2 Feb 94 
p 3 </F>

<F P=103> MK0202142094 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow NEZAVISIMAYA GAZETA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed report] </F>
  [Text] Yesterday another round of Russian-Estonian 
interstate talks began in Nakhabino, near Moscow. The program 
of discussion includes military, humanitarian, economic, and 
border problems. The Estonian side is primarily interested in a 
detailed schedule for the pullout of Russian troops from 
Estonia. The Estonian delegation is ready to agree to the 
Russian proposal on the final withdrawal date (31 August 1994) 
only if Estonia gets a schedule providing for a priority pullout 
of combat units and subdivisions. Vasiliy Svirin, chief Russian 
negotiator, said last week that such a detailed document has 
been prepared and it specifies the date for the relocation of 
each military unit. The schedule will be presented during the 
talks. Vyano Reynar, Estonia's ambassador extraordinary and 
plenipotentiary, who has replaced Juri Luik at the post of chief 
Estonian negotiator, has expressed the hope that in spite of a 
number of contradictions, the main treaty on the pullout of 
Russian troops will be ratified after all. At the same time Ago 
Tiyman, the delegation's executive secretary and head of its 
military group, stressed that Estonia would like the Russian 
side not to link economic and political problems, in particular 
the issue of human rights. It is precisely for this reason, he 
thinks, that the fully elaborated and prepared agreements and 
treaties on economic matters have not been signed yet. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

