<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Negotiator: Estonia Plans To Deport Russian Veterans </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0202185194 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1740 GMT 2 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0202185194 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS diplomatic correspondent Vladimir Taranov] </F>
  [Text] Moscow February 2 TASS -- Estonia refused to discuss 
the possibility of granting the Russian minority the freedom of 
acquiring Estonian citizenship and demanded that a part of 
Russian retired military should withdraw from the republic 
together with the troops. 
  "We hoped that the resolution of the UN General Assembly 
adopted last December, which pointed to unsettled problems in 
Estonia concerning big ethnic groups, mostly Russians, will be 
correctly comprehended in Tallinn", Vasiliy Svirin, head of the 
Russian delegation at talks with Estonia, told a press 
conference on Wednesday after the end of the 16th round of talks. 
  "We called on Estonia to begin a concrete discussion of a 
draft agreement on settling the citizenship problem which has 
been on the negotiating table for two years without any progress 
because Estonia had blocked it", he said and added that the 
Estonian delegation refused to work on the agreement. 
  The document grants Russians in Estonia and Estonians in 
Russia the right to acquire the Estonian or Russian citizenship 
on a free basis. 
  Svirin also said that Estonia demanded that Russian military 
who retired after the abortive Soviet coup in August 1991 be 
withdrawn from the Baltic state together with Russian troops, 
but agreed that 9,670 military who retired before that can count 
on receiving a residence permit. 
  "The issue of deporting a considerable number of retired 
military is put on the agenda", Svirin commented. 
  The deportation problem may diminish the "considerable 
progress" which, according to Svirin, was reached on the draft 
agreement on the Russian pullout. He added that the agreement 
might be initialled in the near future, but the deportation 
problem had now emerged. 
  The Russian chief negotiator said that Russia had for the 
first time warned Estonia, which categorically refuses to 
jointly demarcate the border with Russia, that it has to begin 
doing the job by itself. 

</TEXT>

