<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   No Admission to Council of Europe Before End of 1994 </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0202153494 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1407 GMT 2 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0202153494 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS parliamentary correspondent Ivan Novikov] </F>
  [Text] Moscow February 2 TASS -- Russia can be admitted to 
the Council of Europe not earlier than the end of 1994, 
according to a delegation of the Russian Federal Assembly that 
recently returned from a session of the Council of Europe 
Inter-Parliamentary Assembly in France. 
  The delegation included deputy chairman of the Council of 
the 
Federation, the upper house of the new parliament, Ramazan 
Abdulatipov, Deputies Yevgeniy Ambartsumov, Sergey Baburin, 
Sergey Glotov, Aleksandr Dzasokhov and Vladimir Podoprigora. 
  Russia's admittance to the Council of Europe should be 
preceded by visits to Russia of the heads of some of its 
committees and council leaders, Ambartsumov said. He said the 
visit to France aimed at restoring ties between the Russian 
parliament and the Inter-Parliamentary Assembly which have been 
suspended after the 1993 October revolt in Moscow. "We think 
this goal was achieved," he added. 
  Speaking at a news conference in Moscow on Wednesday, the 
members of the delegation said that Russia's admittance to the 
Council of Europe in being artificially delayed, which signifies 
that Western parliamentarians are concerned about the situation 
in Russia. 
  Abdulatipov stressed that the visit "was a good start of 
coordinated activities of both houses of the Federal Assembly." 
He said the parliament should set up a permanent delegation of 
about 18 people in the interests of future visits. The 
delegation should include representatives of all factions of the 
parliament. 

</TEXT>

