<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   FRY's Information on Military Forces `Welcomed' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PM0302115994 Moscow KRASNAYA ZVEZDA in Russian 3 Feb 94 p 3 </F>
<F P=103> PM0302115994 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow KRASNAYA ZVEZDA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [ITAR-TASS report: "Satisfaction in Moscow"] </F>
  [Text] Moscow, 2 Feb -- The report that the Federal 
Republic of Yugoslavia [FRY] authorities have provided CSCE 
states with information on their military forces -- their status 
as of 1 January 1994 -- for the first time since the collapse of 
former Yugoslavia has been welcomed with satisfaction in Russia. 
This was stated at a briefing by G. Karasin, director of the 
Foreign Ministry Department of Information and the Press. 
  A document distributed by FRY representatives in Vienna 
notes 
that the Yugoslav Army does not plan to deploy additional 
categories of heavy weapons or operational systems on its 
territory in 1994, the Russian Foreign Ministry representative 
reported. 
  "The provision of data about the stationing of troops and 
their armaments in conditions of constant combat action in 
Bosnia and Herzegovina is evidence, in our opinion, of the FRY's 
commitment to solving the problems of military security and 
stability in the region," Karasin noted. 

</TEXT>

