<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Kurils Let Japan, South Korea Fish in Exchange for Fuel </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  MK0202150094 Moscow SEGODNYA in Russian 2 Feb 94 p 11 </F>
<F P=103> MK0202150094 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow SEGODNYA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed report: "South Kurils: Fish in Exchange for </F>
Japanese and Korean Fuel"] 
  [Text] As of 31 January, South Korean and Japanese 
fishermen are permitted to catch, off the South Kurils, up to 10 
percent of fish and seafood procured annually in the area (about 
1.5 million tonnes) in exchange for fuel. Permission was issued 
by the Fishing Industry's Sakhalin Oblast Department on approval 
from the Russian Federation Committee on Fishing in connection 
with a shortage of funds to provide the islands with fuel oil, 
gasoline, and diesel oil. According to Aleksandr Medvedev, head 
of the Sakhalin administration fishing department, the Kurils 
thus will be able to get from Japan and South Korea 45,000 
tonnes of diesel fuel and 15,000 tonnes of fuel oil, quite 
sufficient to solve these islands' energy supply problem. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

