<F P=100> WESTERN REGION </F>
<F P=101> Belarus </F>
<H3> <TI>   Views Shushkevich Shortcomings </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0202185494 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1721 GMT 2 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0202185494 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "Presidential Bulletin" feature: prepared by </F>
Andrey Pershin, Andrey Petrovsky, and Vladimir Shishlin, edited 
by Boris Grishchenko] 
  [Text] The fact that the Belarusian parliament has a new 
leader does not mean that the political and economic policy in 
the republic will be changed. This was stated by the Supreme 
Soviet's Chairman Myecheslaw Hryb at a press conference in Minsk. 
  On a question put by an Interfax correspondent he answered 
that he highly appraised the merits of his predecessor. 
However, he pointed out that Stanislav Shushkevich had lacked 
"persistence in organization of coordinated activities of 
different deputies' groups and factions. This is why the new 
speaker must take this into consideration and correct this." 
  He emphasized that the peace-loving, friendly relations with 
neighbors, aspiration to neutrality and recognition of the 
established borders remained Belarusia's political priorities. 
  Hryb called a more dynamic transition to the market, 
rebuilding of the economy's structure and privatization the main 
domestic task. He recommended that a "serious economist" take 
the post of the Deputy of the Supreme Soviet's Chairman. 
  Hryb proposed that 43-year old Ivan Bambiza be nominated his 
deputy at the parliament's session on Wednesday. His candidacy 
will be discussed in the parliamentary committees and 
commissions. 
  According to the information received by deputies, Bambiza 
was born in the Gomel Region. He graduated from the Belarusian 
Institute of Agricultural machinery and received the diploma of 
a mechanical engineer in 1975. Recently, he has been the head 
of a regional administration and occupied the post of the 
Secretary of the Supreme Soviet's Planning and Budget Financial 
Commission. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

