<F P=100> CENTRAL ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Kazakhstan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Vietnamese Foreign Minister Pays Visit </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD3101184994 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1648 GMT 31 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD3101184994 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By KAZTAG correspondent Ivan Zakharchenko for TASS] </F>
  [Text] Almaty January 31 TASS -- "We welcome Vietnam's 
initiative to set up a joint commission to streamline economic 
relations. This will help expand cooperation in all spheres," 
Kazakhstan's Prime Minister Sergey Tereshchenko said. 
  The statement was made at the meeting with visiting 
Vietnamese Foreign Minister Nguyen Manh Cam in Almaty on Monday. 
  Tereshchenko stressed that Vietnam has accumulated rich 
experience in combating inflation, strengthening currency 
relations and developing the light industry. Kazakhstan and 
Vietnam could cooperate in establishing joint ventures to 
process agricultural produce and produce gas and oil, the prime 
minister added. 
  Kazakhstan has skilled geological cadres and could help 
Vietnam with gas and oil prospecting and training specialists, 
the premier said. 
  The Vietnamese minister recalled that Vietnam was one of the 
first countries to have recognised the independence of 
Kazakhstan. He believes further development of relations would 
be beneficial to both countries. 

</TEXT>

