<F P=100> BALTIC STATES </F>
<F P=101> Estonia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Luik Speaks at Partnership for Peace Signing </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0302114094 Tallinn Radio Tallinn Network in Estonian 1100 
GMT 3 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0302114094 </F>
<F P=104>  Tallinn Radio Tallinn Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Estonian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Estonia today joined NATO's Partnership for Peace 
program, and as with many other eastern European countries, 
stated its wish to eventually become a full member of the North 
Atlantic bloc. Estonian Foreign Minister Juri Luik signed the 
partnership agreement at the NATO headquarters in Brussels. 
  Estonia sees its possible future NATO member status as part 
of a wider European integration framework, Luik said at the 
official signing ceremony. The foreign minister noted that the 
Baltic countries are at the forefront in Europe in the fight for 
democracy and stability, and confirmed that reports coming from 
Moscow [as heard] cause anxiety in Estonia. Luik also stated 
that Estonia wants to have good relations with a democratic 
Russia. Only those countries who are certain of their security 
can be equal [word indistinct] partners for Russia, the foreign 
minister said. He also said that Estonia, Latvia and Lithuania 
form a joint partnership [words indistinct] will be used in 
joint NATO actions within the partnership plan. 

</TEXT>

