<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Economic Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Gerashchenko: 1994 Budget Parameters Not Defined </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0202154294 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1137 GMT 2 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0202154294 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Central Bank Governor Viktor Gerashchenko told 
Interfax in an exclusive interview that the budget parameters 
had not been defined yet for the first quarter of 1994. 
  He said that over the past three weeks the Finance Ministry 
had been trying hard to cut down spending and find new sources 
of income. The Central Bank's and Finance Ministry's common 
task is to make use of available resources and capital through 
economic levers. 
  Although the Central Bank's emission mechanism helps cover 
expenses, it has an inflationary effect and so will therefore be 
used as little as possible, said Gerashchenko. 
  Speaking about the government's pledge to repay the debt of 
4 
Tn rubles to the defense industry, agricultural complex, and 
state-run enterprises in the first quarter of 1994, Gerashchenko 
said that these payments must be made over a longer period. 
Right now the most essential payments should be made, he 
continued. The repayment of those debts which are not so urgent 
should be delayed to avoid an outburst of cash in the first 
quarter of 1994. 
  Gerashchenko described Acting Finance Minister Sergey 
Dubinin 
as someone who realistically approaches difficult problems. 
  See one of the forthcoming issues of Interfax-Exclusive for 
Gerashchenko's complete interview. 

</TEXT>

