<F P=100> Azerbaijan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Baku Spurns Russian-Brokered Cease-Fire </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  MK0202131094 Moscow NEZAVISIMAYA GAZETA in Russian 2 Feb 94 
p 1 </F>

<F P=103> MK0202131094 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow NEZAVISIMAYA GAZETA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Aydyn Mekhtiyev under the "Azerbaijan" rubric: </F>
"Compromise Did Not Materialize. Vladimir Kazimirov Ends Baku 
Visit"] 
  [Text] Azerbaijani leaders have turned down Moscow's 
proposal for a cease-fire in the area of the 
Armenian-Azerbaijani conflict that would have gone into effect 
at 0000 on 1 February. This transpired on the afternoon of 31 
January after the completion of talks in Baku between 
Azerbaijani President Geydar Aliyev and Vladimir Kazimirov, 
chief of the Russian Federation's mediatory mission, who had 
arrived in Azerbaijani capital. According to reports from 
Azerbaijani Foreign Ministry sources, the talks were held in a 
difficult atmosphere. Before noon the Russian diplomat 
discussed the Russian plan for a peaceful settlement with 
Azerbaijani Foreign Minister Gasan Gasanov one on one for more 
than two hours. The two sides considered the possibility of a 
cease-fire to go into force on the night of 1 February along the 
entire front line. 
  Vladimir Kazimirov, who earlier visited Yerevan and 
Khankendi 
(Stepanakert), managed to obtain the Armenian side's agreement 
to the cease-fire. He then had to convince the Baku authorities 
of the need to reciprocate. To all appearances, the meeting of 
the Russian diplomat with the Azerbaijani foreign minister was 
inconclusive. In a press release on the results of the meeting, 
Vladimir Kazimirov said that "the conflicting parties still hold 
uncompromising stances." Nonetheless he expressed his hope that 
a cease-fire agreement would finally be reached and would go 
into force on the night of 1 February. However, Kazimirov's 
meeting with the Azerbaijani president, which took place a bit 
later, confirmed that Baku was unprepared to compromise with the 
Armenian side. After the meeting with the Russian diplomat, 
Geydar Aliyev said that signing a cease-fire agreement would be 
possible only after Armenian troops left occupied Azerbaijani 
territories. According to Aliyev, currently Armenian troops 
occupy seven Azerbaijani districts outside Nagorno-Karabakh, and 
agreeing to negotiate with Armenia before the troop withdrawal 
would mean Azerbaijan's submission to Yerevan's pressure. 
  To all appearances, Azerbaijan's refusal to sign a 
cease-fire 
in the region without preconditions means that a meeting of the 
foreign ministers of Russia, Azerbaijan, and Armenia in Moscow 
scheduled for this week will be postponed indefinitely. 
  An official spokesman for the Russian Foreign Ministry told 
your NEZAVISIMAYA GAZETA correspondent that Moscow was not 
inclined to see the results of the Baku talks as a failure of 
the mediatory mission. In the near future Moscow will continue 
its peacekeeping efforts to broker a truce in the region. 
"Without a cease-fire none of the parties is likely to have its 
demands satisfied," the representative of the Russian Foreign 
Ministry said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

