<F P=100> Azerbaijan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Russian Newspapers Facing Circulation Problems </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PM0302093794 Moscow ROSSIYSKAYA GAZETA in Russian 2 Feb 94 
First Edition p 6 </F>

<F P=103> PM0302093794 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ROSSIYSKAYA GAZETA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Arif Useynov under the "Former Soviet Union" </F>
rubric: "Azerbaijan: Self-Imposed News Blackout"] 
  [Text] Baku -- The situation regarding Russian newspapers 
in Azerbaijan is blighting the lives of tens of thousands of 
subscribers. For the fourth month running they have not 
received LITERATURNAYA GAZETA, KOMSOMOLSKAYA PRAVDA, ARUMENTY I 
FAKTY, and PRAVDA -- these publications were printed in Baku 
until recently. The Azerbmetbuatyayymy Production Association 
makes no secret of who is to blame for this scandal: The 
Azerbaijan Printing House, which is failing to meet its 
contractual obligations, is the prime culprit. 
  It has its own excuses: The Moscow publishing houses do not 
always settle their debts on time and the Moscow plants 
producing printing plates are not delivering their goods. There 
are also problems concerning newsprint. 
  At the same time, the republic's National Bank has not yet 
transferred to the publishing houses of Russia and other CIS 
countries 120 million rubles' worth of subscription fees paid by 
Azerbaijanis for foreign newspapers and magazines in 1994. The 
delivery of Russian newspapers in Azerbaijan is therefore 
altogether problematic. 
  Against the background of all this, the statement by the 
official authorities that the republic is experiencing a news 
blackout is bizarre, to say the least. You get the impression 
that all the obstacles to the distribution of Russian newspapers 
in Azerbaijan are artificially created. 
  The most surprising thing is the lack of realism shown by 
the 
Moscow editorial offices. On top of their disappointed 
expectations, subscribers are also suffering financial losses, 
as nobody is minded to return them their subscription fees. In 
similar situations the Moscow publishing houses have arranged 
for their publications to be delivered by post. Readers may 
have received them late, but they have received them. And what 
is going to happen to the delivery of ROSSIYSKAYA GAZETA and 
NEZAVISIMAYA GAZETA, the number of subscribers to which has shot 
up in Azerbaijan? 
  Here, in addition to applying penalties for breach of 
contract, the Russian newspaper publishing houses could adopt a 
different means of financing the printing and distribution of 
publications in the republic. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

