<H3> <TI>   Duma Committee Position Viewed </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0302203494 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 1740 
GMT 3 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0302203494 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Pavel Kuznetsov] </F>
  [Text] Moscow, 3 Feb -- In the opinion of the members of 
the State Duma's Committee for CIS affairs and links with fellow 
countrymen, the Treaty of Friendship and Cooperation between 
Georgia and Russia, which was signed today in Tbilisi, contains 
a whole range of provisions destabilizing the situation in the 
Caucasus. This is noted in a statement from the committee made 
public by its chairman Konstantin Zatulin at a news conference 
in Moscow. 
  The document notes: There are no grounds to trust the 
capability of the Georgian side to guarantee that the weapons 
will be handled carefully or that the treaty's stipulation on 
not transferring them to third parties will be strictly 
fulfilled. 

