<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Grachev Welcomes Georgia Accord on Military Cooperation </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0402040794 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 2014 GMT 3 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0402040794 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Mikhail Shevtsov] </F>
  [Text] Moscow February 3 TASS -- Russian Defence Minister 
Pavel Grachev has welcomed Russian-Georgian agreements on 
military cooperation signed during President Boris Yeltsin's 
visit to Georgia on Thursday [3 February]. 
  In an exclusive interview with ITAR-TASS, Grachev described 
as one of the main results of the visit the signing of a 
protocol of intent to set up Russian military bases in Georgia. 
Under the protocol, Russia will establish three military bases 
in this Caucasian republic -- in Vazeani, Akhalkalaki and Batumi 
-- by July 1, 1994. They will be staffed mostly with land and 
Air Force troops. 
  Aleksandr Galkin, head of the Russian delegation to the 
talks 
with Georgia, said that Georgia wants Russian troops to stay in 
the republic after 1995 when an agreement on their presence in 
Georgia expires. 
  Galkin said that Russian military presence in Georgia is 
indispensable for ensuring stabilisation of the situation, 
protecting the rights of the Russian-speaking population and 
providing assistance to Georgia to establish its own armed 
forces. 
  The agreement on Russian military bases in Georgia has been 
signed for ten years. After that it can be prolonged by mutual 
consent. The number of troops and weapons at the bases will be 
specified by a special working group later. However, Grachev 
believes that Russia should keep up to 23,000 troops in the 
Transcaucasia, including two thirds of them in Georgia. 
  The sides also agreed that Russia will train military 
specialists for Georgia. According to Galkin, georgia will need 
at least five years to establish its own armed forces. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

