<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Officials Praise Friendship Treaty </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0402095294 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 0843 GMT 4 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0402095294 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent] </F>
  [Text] Moscow February 4 TASS -- President Boris Yeltsin's 
almost lightning-fast visit to the Georgian Republic has yielded 
mutually advantageous and long-ranging solutions to political, 
economic and other problems in relations between Russia and 
Georgia. The many-days-long efforts of politicians and diplomats 
from the two countries were rounded off by the signing of the 
Russo-Georgian Treaty of Friendship, Good-Neighbourly Relations 
and Cooperation. They had to display much persistence in their 
effort to restore the traditional ties of friendship between the 
two countries in spite of the destructive upheavals of past 
years and contrary to the speculations of enemies of the treaty. 
  The leaders and foreign ministries of the two countries have 
exerted titanic efforts in this direction over the past few 
weeks. Assessing the results of their work, Foreign Minister 
Andrey Kozyrev stressed during a recent meeting with leaders of 
the North Caucasian republics that it was neither in the 
interests of Russia, nor of each nation of the North Caucasian 
region to have next to them a state torn asunder by internal 
strife, plunged into an economic chaos and crime. In his 
opinion, the treaty is a key to stability in the entire southern 
region of the Commonwealth of Independent States (CIS). This is 
perhaps the briefest answer to the question: What will the 
treaty give Russia and the Caucasian peoples? 
  "The treaty is primarily important politically for Russia," 
ITAR-TASS was told by member of the Russian Presidential Council 
Emil Pain, "because it is wrong to adhere to two criteria at a 
time in politics: If you are an advocate of Russia's integrity, 
you must be also an advocate of the integrity of neighbouring 
states". Moreover, the current summit talks have shown that the 
treaty gives Russia several purely pragmatic advantages: Access 
to ports, establishment of military bases, maintenance of a 
military-strategic status quo, which is of common importance for 
all the CIS nations. 
  Along with the treaty, which lays a solid legal foundation 
for the entire complex of relations between the two states, 
Russia and Georgia have also signed more than twenty other 
documents. They have also exchanged views on problems linked 
with bilateral cooperation, settlement of conflicts in Abkhazia 
and South Ossetia, on key international problems and on the 
situation in the transcaucasian region as a whole. 
  "The Russian side," President Yeltsin stressed, "stands for 
a 
cardinal improvement of relations with Georgia in all spheres, 
for the quickest possible restoration of ruptured economic, 
cultural, and spiritual contacts, for rapprochement and 
integration. Russia proceeds from the need to honour Georgia's 
territorial integrity and to guarantee fully the interests of 
Abkhazia and South Ossetia." 
  "The documents signed in Tbilisi and the results of the 
summit talks will contribute to the strengthening of cooperation 
not only between our two countries, but among all the nations of 
the Commonwealth of Independent States, too," Eduard 
Shevardnadze, head of the Georgian state, told a press 
conference in Tbilisi. "The importance of President Yeltsin's 
visit transcends the limits of Georgian-Russian relations. 
Their normalisation is closely linked with the settlement of 
all the outstanding problems in the Caucasian and Black Sea 
region, with the achievement of peace and stability there." 
  Asked whether the negotiations touched on Georgia's 
inclusion 
in the rouble zone, President Yeltsin told the press conference 
that it was decided to set up working teams to examine all the 
"pros" and "cons" concerning both Georgia and Russia. 
Journalists put another "difficult question" to Yeltsin: What 
do you think about the State Duma's attitude to the signed 
treaty? The president did not rule out discussions, because 
"any international treaty is subject to debate". "Nevertheless," 
he said, "I am sure that members of the State Duma will 
positively approach this full-scale treaty with the independent 
Republic of Georgia". 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

