<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Troop Withdrawal Talks With Estonia Continue </TI></H3>
<H4>   Official Views `Humiliating' Proposals </H4>
<F P=102> LD0302130594 Tallinn Radio Tallinn Network in Estonian 1800 
GMT 2 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0302130594 </F>
<F P=104>  Tallinn Radio Tallinn Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Estonian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Vasiliy Svirin, leader of the Russian delegation at 
the Estonian-Russian talks, the latest round of which ended 
today, said that Russia intends to link the issue of Russian 
military pensioners rigidly with the troop withdrawal. 
According to Svirin, Estonia demands that the majority of the 
servicemen who retired after 20 August 1991 should leave when 
the army leaves, even if they have no accommodation in Russia. 
The remaining military pensioners must apply to Estonian 
authorities for residence permits. At the same time they are 
required to give a signed declaration saying that they have no 
arms at home and do not intend to obtain any. Retired 
servicemen must also promise not to join any military formations 
nor endanger the state of Estonia through their actions. 
  Svirin stated that such requirements are humiliating. 
  According to Svirin, the Russian side expected to reach an 
agreement on the citizenship issue, but the Estonian delegation 
refused discussion on the matter. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-36237 </DOCNO>
