<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Troop Withdrawal Talks With Estonia Continue </TI></H3>
<H4>   Lack of Withdrawal Plan Noted </H4>
<F P=102> WS0302154694 Tallinn BNS in English 0809 GMT 3 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> WS0302154694 </F>
<F P=104>  Tallinn BNS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tallinn, Feb 02, BNS -- The refusal of the Russian 
negotiators to present a timetable for the withdrawal of troops 
Estonian at the intergovernmental talks on Wednesday [2 
Wednesday] was named as "surprising" by the Estonian Foreign 
Ministry. 
  In its comments on the results of the negotiations released 
late Wednesday, the ministry notes, that the surprise comes 
since a timetable "has been repeatedly promised by Russian 
spokesmen and was even mentioned in Russian President Boris 
Yeltsin's recent letter to Estonian President Lennart Meri". 
  "Since Estonia has fundamentally accepted the August 31, 
1994 
final date offered by the Russians, the logical and necessary 
next step was for Russia to produce a detailed timetable," - 
Estonian Foreign Minister Juri Luik was quoted by the ministry 
as saying. Luik is now in Brussels, where he is to sign the 
Partnership for Peace agreement Thursday. 
  "Estonia still expects Russia to live up to the 
international 
obligations it accepted by signing the Final Document of the 
Helsinki Summit in July 1992, requiring the early, orderly and 
complete withdrawal of foreign military forces from the 
territories of the Baltic states," -- the ministry notes, -- 
"Although there can no longer be talk of an `early' withdrawal, 
the pullout can still be completed completely, unconditionally 
and in an orderly fashion." 

</TEXT>

