<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Troop Withdrawal Talks With Estonia Continue </TI></H3>
<H4>   Estonia Sees `Stumbling Block' </H4>
<F P=102> LD0302145294 Moscow Russian Television Network in Russian 
1100 GMT 3 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0302145294 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow Russian Television Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "Vesti" newscast] </F>
  [Text] The next round of Russian-Estonian talks will take 
place in Tallinn on 1-2 March, Svirin, head of the Russian 
delegation, reported. Correspondent M. Sarbaa reports: 
  Military pensioners in Estonia are a stumbling block at the 
Russian-Estonian talks it was stated today at a news conference 
held at the Estonian Republic Embassy in Moscow on the outcome 
of the 16th round of Russian-Estonian talks which ended 
yesterday. Estonian Ambassador Juriy Kahn said that the Russian 
side had promised to provide a schedule of its troop withdrawal 
from Estonian by this round. The problem of military pensioners 
could delay the final withdrawal of troops set for 31 August of 
this year. 
  In point of fact, Estonia is demanding the deportation from 
the country of approximately 35,000 people, including family 
members of pensioners, to which, of course, Russia will never 
agree. Because of this, the issues of border demarcation, 
Estonia's debt and economic and trade cooperation remain 
unresolved. 
  Work at the talks was carried out by six groups which 
discussed a wide range of problems between Estonia and Russia. 

</TEXT>

