<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Troop Withdrawal Talks With Estonia Continue </TI></H3>
<H4>   Estonian Foreign Ministry Concerned </H4>
<F P=102> LD0302134894 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1143 GMT 3 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0302134894 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] The Estonian Foreign Ministry expressed concern that 
during the Russian-Estonian talks in Moscow Russia did not 
present any schedule for its troops' withdrawal from Estonia. 
  It circulated a statement saying that "as the two parties 
have agreed upon the date of the complete withdrawal in 
principle (August 31, 1994), Estonia hopes that Russia would 
take urgent steps to implement this agreement. 
  During a press conference summing up the results of the 
talks, head of the Russian delegation Vassily Svirin stated that 
Russia had drafted a schedule, but did not pass it to Estonia 
"because Estonia's irreconcilable position hampered the 
coordination of documents on the protection of the retired 
Russian servicemen and their families living in Estonia. 
  The statement also says that the Estonian government 
"demonstrated good will and approved the decree defining the 
procedure for obtaining residence permits by retired foreign 
servicemen and their families." 
  The Estonian Foreign Ministry emphasized that the government 
was motivated by a humane attitude to the individuals who find 
it difficult to return to their homeland because Russia did not 
create proper conditions for this, despite its moral and 
juridical obligations. 
  The Estonian Foreign Ministry qualified the actions of its 
government as a "brave step," because "the Russian troops are 
still located in Estonia, while their strength, including the 
number of retired servicemen, far exceeds the strength of the 
Estonian defence forces." 
  As many as 2,500 Russian servicemen still stay in Estonia. 
The Estonian Defense Forces have about the same number of 
personnel, plus about 2,000 border guards. Estonia's voluntary 
defense organization "Kaitseliit" has about 6,000 men. 
  There are about 11,000 retired Russian servicemen living in 
Estonia. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

