<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Troop Withdrawal Talks With Estonia Continue </TI></H3>
<H4>   Russia Urged To Step Up Withdrawal </H4>
<F P=102> LD0302190094 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1505 GMT 3 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0302190094 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "Diplomatic Panorama" feature: Reports by </F>
Diplomatic Correspondents Dmitriy Voskoboynikov, Igor Porshnev, 
Vitaliy Trubetskoy, and others] 
  [Text] Tallinn understnds the difficulties Russia is 
experiencing in connection with its troops withdrawal from 
Estonia. That is why it agrees to the time for withdrawal fixed 
by the Russian side (before August 31st, 1994: Interfax note), 
and does not insist on an earlier date, Estonia's Ambassador to 
Russia, Yuriy Kahn, told a news conference given on Thursday 
after the latest round of bilateral talks. 
  The Estonian side, he said, has only one wish: that Russia 
step up the withdrawal of units stationed in the center of 
Tallinn which are in direct proximity to the building of 
Estonia's parliament. 
  The diplomat expressed surprise at the Russian delegation's 
refusal to present a schedule for troops withdrawal on the 
grounds that the problem of Russian military retirees in Estonia 
remains unresolved. According to him, earlier the two sides 
agreed "to resort to no linkages, and discuss every issue 
separately." 
  "This road leads to a deadlock. Linkages can only turn the 
negotiating process into bargaining," he said. 
  According to the ambassador, those in the Russian military 
who retired after the time when Estonia gained its independence 
(August 20th, 1991: Interfax's note) must leave Estonia 
together with the withdrawing troops. 
  "It's odd that Russia has not granted these people any legal 
or social guarantees. It seems to have decided to leave them in 
Estonia's care. These people fought for Russia, and such an 
attitude to them on the part of Moscow is inadmissible," he said. 
  With reference to the package of "border issues" Kahn noted 
that Russia "seems to have begun to understand that the 
administrative line fixed by Stalin cannot serve as a state 
border between the two countries." 
  "When determining our border we continue to be guided by the 
peace treaty signed with Russia in Tartu (in 1920: Interfax 
note), and we believe that Moscow has territorial claims to us, 
not vice versa," Kahn said. 
  According to the ambassador, a meeting should be organized 
between the Russian and Estonian presidents "so as to reach 
serious solutions." 
  "Unfortunately, Russia's Foreign Ministry believes that all 
issues should be tentatively coordinated between lower-level 
officials, after which the presidents will only sign the 
documents already drafted. We do not share this approach," the 
diplomat said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-36242 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drsov024_a_94013" </HT>


