</HEADER>

<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Troop Withdrawal Talks With Estonia Continue </TI></H3>
<H4>   Troop Withdrawal Agreement Close </H4>
<F P=102> WS0302185294 Tallinn BNS in English 1614 GMT 3 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> WS0302185294 </F>
<F P=104>  Tallinn BNS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Moscow, Feb 03, BNS -- The delegations of Estonia 
and Russia at the 16th round of intergovernmental talks almost 
completely approved the draft agreement on the withdrawal of 
Russian troops from Estonia. 
  Estonia at the latest round of talks for the first time 
formally accepted Russia's proposal to pull its troops from the 
country by Aug. 31, said the Estonian Ambassador to Russia, Juri 
Kahn. 
  He said the only issue on which the parties had failed to 
reach a final agreement was that of paying compensation. The 
topic has to be settled at the level of heads of state. 
  Russia has said it would agree to call a summit meeting of 
the two countries' leaders only after Estonia provides social 
welfare guarantees for the retired Russian military under the 
conditions set by Russia. 
  Kahn quoted Russian officials as saying their side would not 
present a detailed timetable for the withdrawal of units from 
Estonia until the two countries have agreed on the issue of 
social welfare guarantees for the military who retired after 
Aug. 20, 1991. 
  The ambassador said this latest stance was causing 
bewilderment to Estonia, as the countries earlier had agreed to 
solve any problems one at a time without linking them to one 
another. 
  Kahn dismissed Russia's allegations of Estonia's 
unwillingness to resolve the border issue as groundless. 
"Russia's wish to establish the border along the line where its 
border guards now stand is unacceptable for Estonia," he said. 
He added that Estonia on many occasions had sought taking 
international law as basis for discussion of the border issue. 
  The next round of Estonian-Russian talks is to be held at 
the 
beginning of March. It is possible that Estonian Foreign 
Minister Juri Luik will meet Russian Deputy Foreign Minister 
Vitali Churkin in the meantime, Kahn added. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

