<H3> <TI>   Yeltsin, Nazarbayev To Discuss Baykonur 11-12 Feb </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0302204894 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1807 GMT 3 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0302204894 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Russian and Kazakh negotiators ended the first round 
of their talks on drafting an agreement on the status of 
Baykonur and long term lease of the space launching station to 
Russia. 
  A senior official of the Russian Space Agency who had taken 
part in the talks told Interfax that "the two sides agreed to 
use the draft compiled by Russian experts as the basis for 
further negotiations." 
  A protocol was signed, listing the issues on which full 
agreement had been reached and those on which talks had to 
continue. In particular, no agreement has been reached on which 
country's legislation should apply in the station and which 
country's law enforcement agencies will police there and the 
town of Leninsk. 
  The official emphasized that the Kazakh negotiators needed 
more time to analyze the Russian offer of an amount to be paid 
for use of the launching pads. 
  He did not rule out the possibility that the talks would be 
continued in Almaty, the Kazakh capital. 
  Meanwhile, officials in the Kazakh embassy told Interfax 
that 
the status of Baykonur was likely to be discussed when the 
presidents of the two countries met in Moscow on February 11 and 
12. Nursultan Nazarbayev will have a stopover in Moscow on his 
way to the U.S. 

</TEXT>

