<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Burbulis in Tokyo, Comments on New Cabinet </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW0302091994 Tokyo KYODO in English 0907 GMT 3 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0302091994 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, Feb. 3 KYODO -- Former Russian presidential 
aide Gennadiy Burbulis on Thursday [3 February] conditioned 
cooperation with and support for Russia's new cabinet on its 
pursuit of political and economic reforms. 
  Burbulis, a member of the Russian State Duma, and head of 
the 
humanitarian and political center "Strategia," made the remark 
in an interview with KYODO NEWS SERVICE. 
  He also said reformists must pursue a "more realistic" 
course 
of reforms and acknowledge mistakes that have been made over the 
past two years resulting in bankruptcies and unemployment. 
  More emphasis must be placed on securing the livelihood of 
pensioners and other disadvantaged citizens, he said. 
  In an apparent barb at the new cabinet of Prime Minister 
Viktor Chernomyrdin, Burbulis warned that the country's problems 
cannot be solved by such measures as excessive issuance of 
currency, which would fuel inflation, and reckless issuance of 
subsidies for state farms and industry. 
  He was speaking amid widespread speculation that market 
reforms are threatened by last month's cabinet shakeup and the 
departure of leading free marketeers Yegor Gaydar and Boris 
Fedorov, and Liberal Social Welfare Minister Ella Pamfilova. 
  Chernomyrdin has argued that the reshuffle was necessitated 
by the strong showing of ultranationalists and Communists in 
December's parliamentary elections. 
  Russian President Boris Yeltsin has vowed that reforms will 
continue but has largely distanced himself from the new cabinet. 
  Burbulis, who is a leader of Russia's Choice, the largest 
party in the lower house of the legislature, is visiting Tokyo 
as a member of the Russian delegation to a two-day trilateral 
forum between Russia, Japan and the United States on problems of 
security in the north Pacific, which ended Wednesday. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

