<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Details of Japanese Boats Violating Russian Waters </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0402005394 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 1352 
GMT 3 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0402005394 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Vyacheslav Bantin] </F>
  [Excerpts] Tokyo, 3 Feb -- Colonel General Andrey 
Nikolayev, commander in chief of the Russian border troops, who 
is at present in Tokyo, today showed Russian journalists a video 
recorded by Russian border troops. It clearly shows about 10 
Japanese fishing vessels out of a total of 130 fishing vessels 
which violated the Russian state border on 21 January this year. 
[passage omitted] 
  The video made by the Russian border troops left no doubts 
about the authenticity of the fact that the Japanese fishermen 
violated the Russian Federation state border. The video, made 
with the help of special equipment from a border troops' 
helicopter, clearly shows the registeration numbers and names of 
the vessels, in particular vessels with the numbers 
"H-K-2-20234" and "H-K-2-19082," and the schooners "Kosio-maru," 
"Tayio-maru," and "Nogisinko-maru." The video clearly shows the 
crews of two vessels covering the numbers of their schooners 
with improvised means in order to prevent the Russian border 
troops from recording the numbers. 
  Andrey Nikolayev pointed out in an interview with the 
ITAR-TASS correspondent that he is ready to hand over the video 
to the Japanese officials, including the leadership of the 
Directorate for Security at Sea, if he receives such a request. 
"If there is no such request then we will hand over the video 
to Russian Television on arrival in Moscow," he said. 
  It has become known to the ITAR-TASS correspondent that 
during the first, in Russian-Japanese relations, talks held 
today between the commander in chief of the Russian border 
troops and representatives of the Directorate for Security at 
Sea, the Japanese side was informed that the Russian border 
troops have a video which proves the violation of the Russian 
Federation border on 21 January by Japanese fishing vessels. 
Yet the Japanese border troops failed to ask for the video. 
  It remains completely unknown what other issues were 
discussed at Andrey Nikolayev's meeting with his Japanese 
colleagues. Informed sources have told the ITAR-TASS 
correspondent that the Japanese side insisted that there should 
be total confidentiality at the talks and that their contents 
should not be made public. According to sources, this is 
connected with the fact that Japan's attitude toward direct 
contacts with Russian border troops -- a country with which 
Japan still does not have a peace treaty, and that means no 
state border -- remains sufficiently painfully sensitive. 
[passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

