<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Border Guards To `Suppress' Violations in Far East </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0302154094 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1428 GMT 3 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0302154094 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Vyacheslav Bantin] </F>
  [Text] Tokyo February 3 TASS -- Russian border troops "will 
use in full measure the rights granted to then by Russian 
legislation" to suppress any violations of the border of the 
Russian Federation in the Far East, the Commander in Chief of 
the Russian Border Troops Andrey Nikolayev said in Tokyo today. 
  Nikolayev added that this also meant the use of firearms 
against transgressors if they failed to obey orders by border 
guards. 
  As concerns the mass violation of the Russian border near 
the 
southern Kuril Islands by Japanese shipping vessels on January 
21 and 22, Nikolayev said that the transgression of the Russian 
border by 130 Japanese boats must have been preplanned. To all 
appearances, it was a reaction to the detention of a Japanese 
schooner under Captain Keinichi Noto by Russian coast guards in 
the same area at the end of November. Firearms were used after 
the Japanese captain declined to obey orders. He was wounded. 
  Nikolayev said Keinichi Noto will soon face trial by a 
Russian court which will decide on the fate of the captain and 
his schooner. 
  Soon after Captain Noto's schooner was detained, the 
Japanese 
Ministry of Foreign Affairs demanded in a note to Moscow that 
the captain and two sailors, as well as the boat, be released. 
The two sailors returned to Japan in January. 
  Nikolayev stressed that the Russian border units in the Far 
East "will protect the state border in accordance with the 
principles defined by the Russian president and government". 
  "No one should have any doubts that we will firmly guard our 
country's economic interests," he said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

