<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Foreign Ministry Spokesman Holds News Briefing </TI></H3>
<H4>   Comments on Resolving DPRK Nuclear Issue </H4>
<F P=102> LD0302191094 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1719 GMT 3 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0302191094 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS diplomatic correspondents Boris Krivoshey and </F>
Denis Perkin] 
  [Text] Moscow February 3 TASS -- Possibilities of resolving 
the nuclear problem in North Korea have not exhausted and, 
therefore, it is necessary to continue discussing all questions 
at the negotiation table, Russian Deputy Foreign Ministry 
Spokesman Mikhail Demurin told a briefing held on Thursday [3 
February]. 
  Touching on the Russian side's participation in finding a 
solution to the nuclear problem in North Korea, Demurin said 
that Russia is working in three directions. It supports a 
dialogue between North Korea and the United States, North Korea 
and the International Atomic Energy Agency (IAEA), as well as 
North and South Koreas. 
  "It is fully possible to resolve the problem of the 
non-proliferation of nuclear weapons in the Korean Peninsula by 
acting in these directions. The basis of the solution should be 
a strcit observance of obligations of the agreement on 
guarantees with the iaea by Pyongyang," the Russian deputy 
foreign ministry spokesman emphasised. 
  "Russia is for North Korea remaining faithful to the Nuclear 
Weapon Non-Proliferation Treaty, and we also underscore the need 
to put into action the joint declaration about denuclearization 
of the Korean Peninsula by the North and South," Mikhail Demurin 
concluded. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

