<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   NATO Commander Ends Visit to Moscow </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0302220194 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1910 GMT 3 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0302220194 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondents Vladimir Gondusov and Sergey </F>
Ostanin] 
  [Text] Moscow February 3 TASS -- Commander-in-chief of NATO 
Forces in Central Europe General Henning von Ondarza ended his 
four-day visit to Moscow on Thursday [3 February]. 
  Von Ondarza, 60, who is to retire in April 1994, expressed 
satisfaction with the results of his visit and confessed that he 
had always looked at the Soviet Union and its allies through 
"the gun sight." His visit has become possible due to the 
political thaw in relations between the east and west, he said. 
  In Moscow the general met with Vladimir Semenov, commander 
of 
the Russian land forces, Mikhail Kolesnikov, chief of the 
Russian General Staff, and other officials. 
  He welcomed Kolesnikov's words that "the General Staff of 
the 
Russian armed forces is studying the Partnership for Peace 
programme with interest. It contains good ideas. The practical 
realisation of this programme will speed up our rapprochement 
with the North- Atlantic Alliance." 
  The NATO general said NATO is ready to provide assistance to 
the peace-keeping forces of Russia and the CIS, including to 
train specialists for work in areas of inter-ethnic conflicts as 
observers. 
  Von Ondarza's visit was part of the Russia-NATO programme of 
military cooperation which envisages over 50 joint projects in 
1994, including senior officer and expert exchanges, joint 
military manoeuvres and other events. 

</TEXT>

