<F P=101> International Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Seized at Rostov Airport </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0302220794 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1807 GMT 3 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0302220794 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] The operation for the release of the hostages taken 
by a terrorist in Sukhodolsk on Thursday (formerly Krasnodon, 
the Ukrainian region of Lugansk) has practically come to an end 
in the airport in Rostov-on-Don. Well-informed sources told 
INTERFAX that the terrorist, who called himself Nikolay 
Skvortsov, was seized. 
  He had kept two boys, ages 3 and 4, and their 28-year-old 
nursery school teacher, Natalia Khitalenko, as hostages. 
  The terrorist, who had also captured a YAZ car with a 
driver, 
demanded on Thursday morning that $500,000 and a plane to go 
abroad be given to him. 
  He went from Sukhodolsk to Rostov-on-Don together with the 
hostages. Authorities there agreed to give him a Tu-134 
aircraft. 
  Initially, he declared that negotiations would begin as soon 
as he boarded the plane. He also demanded that he and the 
hostages board the plane before the crew. Two crews had 
volunteered to pilot the plane. 
  According to some sources, the terrorist intended to leave 
for London. Other information says he was going to the U.S.A. 

</TEXT>

