<F P=100> National Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Urges `Economic Union' With Russia </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0402095794 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 0928 GMT 4 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0402095794 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent] </F>
  [Text] Moscow February 4 TASS -- Newly elected Crimean 
President Yuriy Meshkov said his first step will be the 
restoration of a close economic union with Russia and that he 
always considered the people of the peninsula to be a part of 
the Russian people. 
  "My first step will be the creation of an authoritative 
delegation which would go to Moscow to conclude a close economic 
and cultural union with Russia", he said in an interview with 
the business "VEK" (CENTURY) newspaper on Friday. 
  The Crimea was handed over to Ukraine by former Soviet 
communist leader Nikita Khrushchev in 1954, but Meshkov believes 
the people of the peninsula remained a part of the Russian 
people. 
  "As far as the Russian people are concerned -- I believe 
that 
before and after 1954 the people of the Crimea were a part of 
the Russian people. I hope the restoration of unity, 
unification is an issue of the near future", he stressed. 
  Meshkov who was inaugurated on Friday insists that the 
Crimea 
should hold a referendum on independence despite the ban of 
Ukrainian authorities. 
  "The acting ban of Kiev on holding the referendum has no 
grounds", he said adding that enough signatures had been 
collected in the Crimea in favour of holding the plebiscite. 
  "The talk is about the right of the Crimea to independently 
determine the contents and forms of its relations with 
neighbouring states", Meshkov said. 
  The president also said that the Black Sea Fleet which is 
disputed between Russia and Ukraine should not be split and 
should remain Russian. However, he added that the fleet should 
help create the Ukrainian Navy. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

