<F P=100> National Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Supreme Council Adopts Law on Local Elections </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0402094994 Kiev UNIAN in Ukrainian 1630 GMT 3 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0402094994 </F>
<F P=104>  Kiev UNIAN </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Ukrainian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Kiev -- A plenary session of the Supreme Council of 
Ukraine took place on 3 February, at the beginning of which a 
law "On the Formation of Local Bodies of Power and 
Self-Government" was adopted. The law envisages in particular 
the division of power into bodies of local self-government and 
bodies of state power. The chairmen of oblast, rayon, town, 
settlement and village councils are directly elected by the 
populace, and in accordance with their post they head the 
executive committees of the relevant councils and have dual 
subordination. The chairmen of councils and the executive 
bodies they head are accountable to and under the control of the 
relevant councils, but on issues of carrying out the authorities 
of state executive power delegated to them they are subordinate 
to the Cabinet of Ministers of Ukraine. The last article of the 
law envisages that after elections of deputies and chairmen of 
councils and the formation of executive bodies, the law of 
Ukraine "On the Representative of the President of Ukraine" will 
become invalid. A separate resolution envisages that elections 
of deputies to village and oblast councils and their chairmen 
will be conducted at the same time as the election of the 
president of Ukraine on 26 June 1994. 
  According to Ivan Plyushch, chairman of the Supreme Council, 
the issue of amendments and additions to the law on elections of 
people's deputies of Ukraine was put to the vote for the seventh 
time on 3 February. But this time the voting did not yield 
positive results. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

