<F P=100> National Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Draft Constitutional Law Considers President's Functions </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0302224594 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1822 GMT 3 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0302224594 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "Presidential Bulletin" feature No. 23 (513)] </F>
  [Text] A draft constitutional law on power which was 
considered by the Ukrainian parliament on Thursday morning 
attributes more representative functions to the post of the 
president. 
  As a member of the parliamentary commission on legislature 
and law Sergey Sobolev told the news agency Interfax-Ukraine, 
"the president becomes the head of state and represents Ukraine 
in international affairs, signs international treaties, and is 
entitled to cancel decisions of the Cabinet and implement a 
number of other duties." 
  The supreme body of the executive power in the republic is 
the Cabinet, which is confirmed by the parliament. As a result, 
Sobolev said, "Ukraine actually becomes a parliamentary 
republic." 
  The draft law on power also envisages that all authorities 
in 
regions are transferred to chairmen of local executive bodies, 
which should be elected popularly. The institution of 
presidential representatives in this case is eliminated. 
  Speaking at a session of the Supreme Soviet the day before, 
its Chairman, Ivan Plyushch, spoke against holding a referendum 
on basic constitutional provisions about power in Ukraine on 
March 27. Earlier, this proposal was made by President Leonid 
Kravchuk. 
  Plyushch believes that amendments to the organization of 
state power in Ukraine "should be made not through a referendum, 
but through the adoption of a constitutional law." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-36295 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drsov024_f_94005" </HT>


