<H3> <TI>   People's Accord Party Urges Elections, Backs Strikes </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  WS0302154294 Minsk BELAPAN in Belarusian 1406 GMT 3 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> WS0302154294 </F>
<F P=104>  Minsk BELAPAN </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Belarusian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed report: "News Conference of the Party of </F>
People's Accord Leadership"] 
  [Text] Today, at the National Press Center, the Party of 
People's Accord [PNZ] leadership held a news conference. 
Chairman Henadz Karpenka said that the primary PNZ task is to 
nominate candidates for the future elections to the Supreme 
Soviet. Henadz Karpenka also said that the PNZ will urge 
pre-term elections and changes in the structure of the 
Belarusian Council of Ministers. The PNZ chairman expressed full 
support for the strike which was scheduled by the Free Trade 
Unions to begin on 15 February. The reason for this is the 
Council of Ministers' unwillingness to hold talks with trade 
unions and adopt a mutually acceptable resolution. According to 
Karpenka's words, the PNZ held consultations with trade unions 
last Saturday [29 January]. With regard to the economic 
situation in the country, Henadz Karpenka stated that its change 
will be accompanied by a sharp worsening of the people's living 
standard. H. Karpenka said that presidential elections are 
necessary; however, they should be organized not by the Supreme 
Soviet, but by the people. PNZ Deputy Chairman Alaksey Karol, 
while commenting on the dismissal of Supreme Soviet Chairman 
Stanislav Shushkevich, stated that this [dismissal] has 
strengthened the authoritarian basis and brought a shift toward 
an authoritarian style of governing and the monopolization of 
power in the government's hands. 

</TEXT>

