<F P=100> Georgia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Protocol Signed on Setting Up 3 Russian Bases </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0302135194 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1143 GMT 3 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0302135194 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Russia's Defence Minister Pavel Grachev and 
Georgia's Chief of Staff Guram Nickolaishvili signed in Tbilisi 
on Thursday, February 3, a protocol of intent, which provides 
for setting up three Russian military bases in Georgia. 
  As Grachev has reported in an interview with Interfax, the 
facilities are to be located at Vaziani (30 kilometers south of 
Tbilisi), at Akhalkalaki (southern Georgia), and at Batumi (the 
Ajar Autonomous Republic). 
  As he explained, the bases will get under construction in 
1995 after the term of Russian troops interim presence expires, 
and their status will differ much from that of the Russian 
forces in Georgia now. Russia will foot the entire troops 
maintenance bill and will partly compensate for its military 
presence in Georgia. 
  Grachev emphasized that the primary goal of the bases would 
be to defend the CIS North Caucasian flank. 
  According to experts, there are about 8000 Russian 
servicemen 
in Georgia. With the formation of three bases in Georgia plus 
two facilities in Armenia and Azerbaijan, the Russian army in 
Transcaucasia will total 23,000 men. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

