<F P=100> Georgia </F>
<H3> <TI>   South Ossetian, Abkhaz Stance on Treaty `Incorrect' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0302154194 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1341 GMT 3 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0302154194 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondents Yuriy Sizov and Gennadiy </F>
Talalayev] 
  [Text] Tbilisi February 3 TASS -- The full-scale treaty of 
friendship and cooperation signed by Russia and Georgia today, 
which is seen as "most useful to Russia in its political aspect" 
by Russian Presidential Council member Emil Paine, has met cool 
reception in Abkhazia and South Ossetia, Georgia's autonomies 
claiming greater independence. 
  Paine called their attitude "incorrect" from Russia's 
viewpoint for two reasons: "It is wrong to stick to double 
criteria in politics: if you support territorial integrity of 
Russia, you must support territorial integrity of the 
neighboring states -- there is no alternative," Paine said. "And 
it is wrong to condition the signing of an inter-state treaty on 
the settlement of internal conflicts. Problems of this kind 
exist in many countries. It is difficult to imagine someone 
order other countries not to have anything to do with Russia 
until its federal authorities settle relations with the Chechen 
Republic, for example". 
  As concerns benefits for Russia, Paine said Russia needs sea 
ports badly. Georgia has several and can provide the 
much-needed services to Russia. 
  Paine also pointed to the problem of Russian troops and 
military bases on Georgian territory. "Georgia guarantees 
required provisions for the Russian troops," he said. The two 
countries's agreement on military strategic issues is of 
significance for all Commonwealth member-countries. 
  The drawing of new borders could cost Russia tens of 
billions 
of roubles. Also important are the agreements with Georgia on 
transit transportation of Russian goods by land and sea via 
Georgia, Paine said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

