<F P=100> Georgia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Poti Port To Become Joint-Stock Company </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU0302110294 Tbilisi SAKARTVELOS RESPUBLIKA in Georgian 28 
Jan 94 p 1 </F>

<F P=103> AU0302110294 </F>
<F P=104>  Tbilisi SAKARTVELOS RESPUBLIKA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Georgian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Eduard Ediberidze: "In the Cabinet of Ministers. </F>
From Principled and Serious Positions"] 
  [Excerpt] The commercial port of Poti is to become the 
biggest joint-stock company in Georgia. The Georgian Cabinet of 
Ministers agreed in principle to transforming this state 
enterprise, the biggest in the republic, into a joint-stock 
company during its regular session held on 26 January under the 
chairmanship of Prime Minister Otar Patsatsia. Out of the whole 
block of shares of this future joint-stock company, which, 
according to preliminary calculations, will amount to 307.8 
billion rubles, 51 percent will be kept by the state while the 
remaining 49 percent will be owned by the port's collective, 
Poti city administration, and others wanting to buy shares both 
in the near abroad and in other foreign countries. This will 
provide the opportunity to attract solid investments for both 
the port and the city and the development of its infrastructure. 
It is significant that it is planned to organize the 
registration of shares in the port of Poti at the world's 
leading stock exchanges. The port, which assumes the function 
of a key base along the Eurasian transport corridor, will serve 
not only Georgia but also Armenia and Azerbaijan and 12 more 
countries. As Deputy Prime Minister Zurab Kervalishvili said, 
it is planned that, following the port's reconstruction and 
expansion and the building of new terminals, the volume of 
freight traffic handled by it will increase from between 3 and 4 
million to 15 million tonnes within the next two years alone. 
Moreover, according to estimates, this will ensure that the 
republic receives $120 million. 
  It was the unanimous opinion of those participating in the 
session that the transformation of the port of Poti into a 
joint- stock company should become a model for all state 
enterprises and organizations that are to become joint-stock 
companies. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

