<H3> <TI>   Nationalist Leader Congratulates Zhirinovskiy </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  MK0302143594 Moscow KURANTY in Russian 3 Feb 94 p 3 </F>
<F P=103> MK0302143594 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow KURANTY </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Inga Abgarova report under the general headline: "V.V.Zh. </F>
Has Given Georgia to Turkey... But They Do Not Know it Yet in 
Georgia"] 
  [Text] For all the variety of party movements in Georgia 
and serious differences of views between loyalists of one party 
or another, they all met Vladimir Zhirinovskiy's victory in the 
Russian elections with unanimous silence. Only Zurab Gagnidze, 
candidate of philosophic sciences and leader of the Georgian 
National Ideology Party, has sent a congratulatory telegram to 
Vladimir Volfovich on behalf of his supporters. "We are 
confident that your victory will have a positive influence on 
the attainment of genuine freedom in Georgia," the telegram 
says. "Zhirinovskiy is a nationalist in the good sense of the 
word," Gagnidze believes. We concluded from a conversation with 
the leader of national ideologists that he is attracted by the 
Liberal Democrats' economic program, Zhirinovskiy's desire to 
cut down the bureaucracy, and his struggle against American 
aggression. Zurab Gagnidze opposes the withdrawal of Russian 
troops from Georgia, saying that there has been not a single 
serious conflict in the decades while Russian soldiers were 
present here. 

</TEXT>

