<F P=100> CENTRAL ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Kazakhstan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Nazarbayev on Relationship With Russia, CIS </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PM0302145194 Moscow SELSKAYA ZHIZN in Russian 3 Feb 94 p 3 </F>
<F P=103> PM0302145194 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow SELSKAYA ZHIZN </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by ITAR-TASS correspondents Nikita Yermakov and </F>
Konstantin Pribytkov: "Kazakhstan's Future Is With Russia"] 
  [Text] When Kazakhstan was part of the Soviet Union, few 
people were familiar with it, and from this point of view 
participation in the Davos World Economic Forum provides an 
opportunity to showcase the republic, its potential, its 
legislation, and its development potential, President Nursultan 
Nazarbayev of Kazakhstan said in an interview with ITAR-TASS 
correspondents. 
  At first the West did not understand the real situation in 
the economies of the CIS countries, the Kazakhstani head of 
state went on to say. Now it is starting to understand the 
realities taking shape in the CIS. If I myself had not believed 
in the Commonwealth's potential, I would never have been a 
fervent supporter of the integration process. The fact that the 
ruble zone, for which I also fought, has collapsed attests to 
what has now become clear: We are different. The economies and 
the states are different. We have become really independent 
states. Some people, maybe among the Russian political 
establishment, dislike this. As for Kazakhstan, I firmly 
declare (not because I am afraid or apprehensive of something or 
because I am engaging in intrigue): Strategically, Kazakhstan's 
future is with Russia. The future of the people, the future of 
the state, the future of the economy. This is not only 
advantageous to Kazakhstan, it is also advantageous to Russia. 
If we speak of independence, Russia was the first to proclaim 
sovereignty in 1990. I was astounded at the time: from whom, 
from what? But what is there to be surprised at now? 
  I do not regard sovereignty and independence as an end in 
itself, the president went on to point out. The end is to 
improve people's lives and the economy through this. When any 
state signs some agreement, it assumes obligations and gives up 
part of its sovereignty. The CIS countries' integration must 
now proceed along a path similar to the West European one, as 
the EC is doing. They are all independent states in the EC, and 
they all have their own currency, political independence, and 
freedom. Here, I believe, fate itself has determined a very 
important place for Russia. Russia can act as a unifier by fully 
recognizing sovereignties and not exerting any pressure, and 
maybe it can forgo some things at first. We must do as the West 
Europeans did, only not travel this path in 30 years, like they 
did, but in a shorter space of time. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
