<F P=100> CAUCASUS </F>
<F P=101> Armenia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Azerbaijani Planes Bomb Karabakh Settlements </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  NC0302151894 Yerevan Armenia's Radio First Program Network 
in Armenian 1400 GMT 3 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> NC0302151894 </F>
<F P=104>  Yerevan Armenia's Radio First Program Network 
in Armenian 1400 GMT 3 Feb 94 </F>



<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105>Armenian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Despite lessening tension on the Karabakh fronts, 
the Azerbaijani troops are still trying to advance in several 
directions. 
  The Nagorno-Karabakh Republic Defense Army Press Service 
reported that large enemy forces, mostly armored cars, launched 
an attack yesterday against Karabakh positions in the direction 
of Martuni and Gadrut. The offensive lasted from morning until 
late at night. After losing five tanks and 30 soldiers on the 
battlefield, the Azerbaijani troops retreated to their initial 
positions. Two Karabakh fighters died and seven were wounded. 
  Relative calm prevailed on the other sectors of the front 
until noon today. 
  The same source reported that an Azerbaijani Air Force plane 
appeared over Karabakh at around 1030 today. According to 
preliminary reports, the enemy plane was most probably engaged 
in a reconnaissance flight. Azerbaijani attack planes bombed 
the settlements in Askeranskiy Rayon at 1100. Casualty figures 
are being determined. 
  The Armenian Defense Ministry Press Service has reported 
that 
the calm prevailing on the border for the past three days has 
not been violated. We talked with the Press Service a short 
time ago and were informed that the situation on the border 
remained unchanged at 1930. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

