<F P=100> Federal Assembly </F>
<H3> <TI>   Chernomyrdin No-Show Indicates `Lack of Respect' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PM0302170694 Moscow IZVESTIYA in Russian 4 Feb 94 First 
Edition p 1 </F>

<F P=103> PM0302170694 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow IZVESTIYA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Aleksandra Lugovskaya report: "Senators Demand Premier's </F>
Appearance"] 
  [Text] V. Chernomyrdin's expected speech in the Federation 
Council did not take place 3 February. 
  The prime minister's refusal to come and give information 
about government policy was regarded by the senators not only as 
a lack of respect for the upper house of parliament but also as 
a political gesture. 
  It was maybe the first time the deputies had used such harsh 
terms in demanding that V. Shumeyko explain why the meeting was 
shelved. In response the speaker cited the most diverse 
arguments. Specifically, that without a discussion of this 
question at a special government session Chernomyrdin's speech 
would be of an unofficial nature and would reflect his personal 
viewpoint. That a session of the Cabinet of Ministers Presidium 
had begun on the morning of 3 February. In addition, it was 
learned that the premier is flying to Minsk in the evening while 
O. Soskovets, his first deputy, is in Georgia. And that Economy 
Minister A. Shokhin will speak in the Federation Council. 
  Shumeyko reminded all his colleagues that it is his job as 
speaker to conduct sessions and keep order, not to deliver the 
premier there. 
  But Shumeyko's arguments merely added fuel to the fire: Even 
sterner words followed from the microphones -- about the 
Federation Council's role and place in Russia's political life. 
For example, a deputy from Udmurtia said that he is not greatly 
concerned by what is happening in Belarus -- right now there is 
a crisis situation in his own Udmurtia and in Russia as a whole: 
"We want to know our government's actions in the next few days." 
  After a heated debate the senators again instructed the 
speaker to hold talks with the premier and to inform him during 
the recess of the house's insistent wish to see him on the 
Federation Council platform on 3 February. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-36329 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drsov024_c_94005" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-SOV-94-024 </AU>
Document Type:Daily Report 
<DATE1>  4 Feb 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> Federal Assembly </F>
<H3> <TI>   Federation Council To Resume 18 Feb </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0302230194 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1939 GMT 3 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0302230194 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] At its evening session today, the Federation Council 
discussed the status of its deputies and issues related to the 
maintenance of their activities. The deputies decided to return 
to the consideration of their status later, since the State Duma 
had not yet passed the law "On the status of the deputy of the 
Federal Assembly." 
  The session approved the structure of the chamber's staff 
and 
set their salaries equal to those of government support staff. 
Each deputy will have an unlimited number of assistants and 
manage a fund equal to 80 minimum salaries plus guaranteed 
bonuses and compensations to pay their salaries out of. 
  The Federation Council scheduled its next session for 
February 18. 
  The draft agenda of the next meeting includes discussing the 
findings of the council's commission in the area of the 
Ossetian-Ingush conflict, approving the composition of 
parliamentary committees, looking into the results of the 
activities by the CIS Interparliamentary Assembly and passing a 
plan of legislative activities. The Federation Council also 
plans to invite Prime Minister Viktor Chernomyrdin on the same 
day. 
  As was announced before, Russian President Boris Yeltsin is 
expected to make his annual address to the Federal Assembly on 
social and economic policies on February 18. 

</TEXT>

