<F P=100> Federal Assembly </F>
<H3> <TI>   State Duma Session Opens; Agenda Outlined </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0402091194 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 0809 GMT 4 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0402091194 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS parliamentary correspondent Ivan Novikov] </F>
  [Text] Moscow February 4 TASS -- A regular plenary meeting 
of the State Duma, the lower chamber of the Russian parliament, 
opened here today. 
  According to the preliminary agenda, handed out to MPs 
before 
the meeting, the Duma is to hear an information [as received] on 
decisions adopted by the chamber's council, a report of the 
Mandate Commission on changes in the composition of the State 
Duma, and also to discuss a bill "on the publication and entry 
into force of federal constitutional laws, federal laws, and 
acts of the two chambers of the Federal Assembly", and a draft 
resolution to "ensure the work of the State Duma". 
  The Duma is also expected to endorse the composition of its 
delegation to a meeting of the Council of the CIS 
Interparliamentary Assembly, scheduled to meet in St. Petersburg 
from February 8-9. 
  The agenda also includes the so-called "government hour", 
during which the Duma is expected to hear a report by Central 
Bank Chairman Viktor Gerashchenko and newly-appointed Finance 
Minister Sergey Dubinin on ways to settle the crisis of 
non-payments. 
  It is not ruled out that the MPs will also hear several 
political statements by parliamentary factions. This item also 
figures in the Duma's parliamentary agenda. 
  Aleksandr Yakovlev, the Russian president's plenipotentiary 
representative to the Federal Assembly (parliament), will be 
presented to the MPs today. 

</TEXT>

