<F P=100> Federal Assembly </F>
<H3> <TI>   Duma Postpones Debate on Amnesty Edict </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0302133894 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1143 GMT 3 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0302133894 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] The State Duma's Council, comprising its Chairman, 
his deputies, and the factions leaders, has decided to put off 
the presidential amnesty decree indefinitely. The earlier-set 
discussion date was Friday, February 4. 
  The amnesty declaration was prompted by the adoption of 
Russia's Constitution on December 12, 1993. According to the 
basic law, the right to declare amnesty rests with the Duma, the 
Lower House of the Federal Assembly, parliament in Russia. 
  Drafted by the Russian President's State Management 
Department, the decree provides for pardoning certain categories 
of prisoners, World War Two veterans and women included. 
  No faction has unequivocally supported the decree. Yegor 
Gaydar, the leader of "Russia's Choice," has suggested in an 
interview with Interfax that amnesty should be carried out in 
line with specific penal code clauses rather than categories of 
prisoners. 
  At a news-conference a week ago, the LDP faction's leader 
Vladimir Zhirinovskiy reiterated his faction's call for freeing 
all political convicts and those jailed for economic 
mismanagement as of March 1985. "What Russia's president wants 
to do at this time is to pardon criminals," he stressed. 
  The faction of communists and agrarians intend to press for 
the release of all those charged for complicity in the events of 
August 1991 and October 1993. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

