<F P=100> BALTIC STATES </F>
<F P=101> Estonia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Officials on Cooperation With NATO </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0302230894 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1939 GMT 3 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0302230894 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] A team of NATO officials sent to determine to what 
extent Estonia was prepared to join the Partnership for Peace 
program has ended its visit there. 
  Estonian Defense Minister Indrek Kannik said at a news 
conference Thursday that the mission members discussed with 
Estonian officials ways to step up the country's cooperation 
with NATO, in particular the setting up of a consulting 
mechanism which would work in crisis situations, joint military 
exercises and training of Estonian officers. They also 
discussed what Estonia could offer NATO. 
  Hermann von Richthoff, the mission head, emphasized that 
Partnership for Peace was not hostile to any country. He said 
that joint exercises with NATO could be staged in Estonia in 
1993 [as received]. 
  General K.-T. Steinkopf, a mission member, said that NATO 
could not sell weapons to countries that were not its members 
but Baltic states could buy them from NATO members in bilateral 
deals. 
  The NATO team has left for Latvia from where it will go on 
to 
Ukraine and Moldova. 

</TEXT>

