<F P=100> Lithuania </F>
<H3> <TI>   President `Very Concerned' by Brain Drain </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  WS0302154494 Tallinn BNS in English 0809 GMT 3 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> WS0302154494 </F>
<F P=104>  Tallinn BNS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Vilnius, Feb 02, BNS -- Lithuanian President 
Algirdas Brazauskas said he is very concerned that trained 
specialists are moving to private structures and thus weaken the 
scientific potential of research institutes and institutions of 
higher education. 
  Speaking at the annual Lithuanian Science and Industry 
conference in Kaunas Tuesday [1 February], the president 
emphasized the need to preserve the remaining scientific nucleus 
and to train new specialists for the country. 
  Prime Minister Adolfas Slezevicius admitted in his report 
that the state is unable to maintain all scientific personnel. 
  The number of scientific personnel decreased by nearly 30 
percent over the past three years, but, in the premier's view, 
the country's higher education institutions do not experience a 
shortage of specialists yet. 
  The four-day conference in Kaunas will try to find solutions 
to problems of developing Lithuanian science and will search for 
a way out a crisis that was caused by the worsening economic 
situation. The conference is attended by members of the 
government, university rectors and scholars. 

</TEXT>

