<F P=100> Latvia </F>
<H3> <TI>   U.S. Security Said Tied to Latvian-Russian Pact </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  WS0302173194 Tallinn BNS in English 1353 GMT 3 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> WS0302173194 </F>
<F P=104>  Tallinn BNS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Riga, Feb 03, BNS -- The signature of a 
Latvian-Russian agreement on troops' withdrawal will entitle 
Latvia to receive international security guarantees from the 
United States and European countries, Foreign Minister Georgs 
Andrejevs told reporters Thursday [3 February]. 
  The United States pledges to send Latvia internationally 
recognized experts to monitor the agreement's implementation, 
said Saeima (parliament) Foreign Committee head Alexander 
Kirsteins. 
  Latvia's Way's Andrejs Pantelejevs underlined that Latvian 
security was important not only to his country but also to 
American and European security, judging by the results of this 
week's meetings in Washington. 
  The U.S. Government confirmed its interestedness in the 
conclusion of a formal agreement between Latvia and Russia on 
the withdrawal of the Russian troops and the dismantling of the 
Skrunda radar station. 
  The Russian Government promised the United States to get the 
remaining troops out of Latvia until the end of August on 
condition Latvia allows it retain the Skrunda radar for four 
years and 18 months. 
  If Latvia rejects the term and follows its own way to reach 
an accord with Russia, the United States declines to extend any 
subsequent security guarantees. 
  Latvia, however, will accept the proposal only if the new 
building of the Skrunda early-warning antimissile installation 
will be pulled down immediately, said Pantelejevs. 
  The United States supports Latvia's signature to NATO's 
Partnership for Peace program and will help Latvia with 
technical provisions, Kirsteins said. 
  The Latvian delegation met with President Bill Clinton, 
State 
Secretary Warren Christopher, Deputy State Secretary Strobe 
Talbott and Deputy Defense Secretary William Perry. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

