<F P=100> Latvia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Birkavs Stresses Active Participation in NATO </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0302153594 Riga Radio Riga Network in Latvian 1400 GMT 3 
Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0302153594 </F>
<F P=104>  Riga Radio Riga Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Latvian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] [Announcer] State President Guntis Ulmanis and Prime 
Minister Valdis Birkavs today sent a letter to NATO concerning 
Latvia's wish to join the Partnership for Peace program. 
  At a news conference Prime Minister Valdis Birkavs stressed 
that joining this program is one more step in implementing the 
number one priority of the state -- security policy. The 
security and defense policy is currently being implemented in 
Latvia in three main aspects. 
  [Begin Birkavs recording] One is the budget intended for 
defense and security structures. Compared with the past year, 
it has been increased by 57 percent; obviously it is not enough. 
  The second step in that direction is the talks that we have 
begun to also use credits for strengthening our armament. We 
need international guarantees. We have to interweave into the 
European context with all our structures. And the Partnership 
for Peace, this initiative, is the one that gives us new 
opportunities. But I would like to say that that is not a 
security market, on which everyone buys his security, but rather 
that it is an opportunity for a state to achieve gradual 
approach to NATO structures in talks with NATO. That is a 
vehicle that will allow us in the event of a crisis to obtain 
consultations and thus react correctly to specific crises. This 
will require a great deal of strength, this will also require 
additional funds, but this has to be done, because otherwise we 
may lose all that we have achieved. 
  According to the Partnership for Peace, each state can set 
up 
its own communication bureau in Brussels with NATO Headquarters. 
So then, I consider that we will need a person who would be 
specifically oriented toward cooperation with NATO so that we 
can actively participate in the creation of the NATO partnership. 
  The 14th clause of the declaration, Partnership for Peace, 
reads: NATO will provide consultations for each active 
participant in the partnership in the event that they feel 
direct threats to their territorial integrity, political 
sovereignty, or security. 
  So then, a simple passive statement will not be enough and 
we 
are oriented toward active participation in this process. [end 
recording] 
  [Announcer] It is envisaged that Prime Minister Valdis 
Birkavs will sign a document on Latvia joining the Partnership 
for Peace program in Brussels as early as next week. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

