<F P=100> Regional Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Chechnya Prepared To Help Stabilize Caucasus </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0402142094 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1151 GMT 4 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0402142094 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Chechen President Dzhokhar Dudayev said that 
secession of North Caucasus from Russia was a real threat. He 
emphasized in an interview with INTERFAX that this was likely to 
happen unless Russia ceased to use force and blackmail and 
started to use diplomacy and negotiations in its relations with 
the mountain nations. 
  He thinks that Russia is encouraged in its ill-conceived 
North Caucasian policy by "certain quarters in the West who want 
Russia to disintegrate and lose statehood." 
  Dudayev believes that the abundance of weapons and 
uncontrolled militias had contributed to making the region 
unmanageable. This situation affects Russia itself. 
  He said that "weapons are moving from the Caucasus into the 
depths of Russia where armed fascist and nationalist bands are 
formed." 
  In Dudayev's view, "this complicated situation is likely to 
aggravate, making a new Caucasian war possible. Those in the 
Russian leadership who play into the hands of the West and lead 
Russia to a collapse while making a lot of noise about keeping 
it united and indivisible have a significant role to play in 
this process." 
  He said that Chechnya was prepared to look, jointly with 
Russia, for ways to stabilize the Caucasus. 

</TEXT>

