<F P=100> Regional Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Rostov Leaders' Decision on Elections Protested </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PM0402114794 Moscow ROSSIYSKAYA GAZETA in Russian 2 Feb 94 
First Edition p 2 </F>

<F P=103> PM0402114794 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ROSSIYSKAYA GAZETA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Vadim Ogurtsov: "`Don's Choice' Protests"] </F>
  [Text] The inner soviet and administration of the Don have 
adopted a decision on elections to representative bodies of 
state power in Rostov Oblast and organs of local 
self-government. But the "Russia's Choice" territorial bloc, 
which calls itself "Don's Choice" here, has very strongly 
protested the Statutes on Elections to the Legislative Assembly, 
approved by an oblast inner soviet decision. In the first 
place, State Duma deputy B. Titenko and other members of the 
bloc's regional political council stressed at a press 
conference, the inner soviet "adopted" this document after the 
new Russian Constitition depriving the old structure of its last 
juridical rights and powers had come into effect. According to 
the political council, the situation is not remedied by the 
"invitation to representatives of parties and movements," which 
was essentially a variation on "nationwide discussion." The 
Soviet's decision and confirmation followed as before. 
  The blatant breach of the principle of separation of powers, 
since the "statutes," even at local level, do not allow a 
deputy's duties to be combined with work in the executive organs 
of power, is described as the second flaw. 

</TEXT>

