<F P=100> Regional Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Vladimir Oblast Approves Duma Statutes </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PM0402100794 Moscow ROSSIYSKAYA GAZETA in Russian 2 Feb 94 
First Edition p 2 </F>

<F P=103> PM0402100794 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ROSSIYSKAYA GAZETA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Yuriy Shatalov: "Vladimir Preparations"] </F>
  [Text] Vladimir Oblast Administration Chief Yu. Vlasov has 
approved statutes for an Oblast Duma and elections to it. 
  The draft of this document was first discussed in detail at 
an oblast assembly of representatives of various parties, 
movements, and other public organizations, and also power 
structures. There were major objections from assembly 
participants to the administration's proposal to elect 17 
deputies to the future Duma who would work on a permanent basis. 
In that case, the opponents claimed, not all Vladimir Oblast 
rayons would be represented in it, not to mention the fact that 
it would have to operate without standing commissions. But, 
apparently, the representative body henceforth will operate 
without standing commissions, since the final version of the 
statutes on the Oblast Duma provides for 21 deputies. 
  The original draft statutes on elections also underwent 
significant changes. Now someone wishing to register as a 
candidate in an electoral district requires not three but only 
two percent of voters' signatures in his favor. According to 
the statutes, groups of voters, public associations, and 
individuals are entitled to nominate a candidate. 

</TEXT>

