<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Yeltsin Warned Duma May Not Ratify Georgia Treaty </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0302203994 Moscow Russian Television Network in Russian 
1700 GMT 3 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0302203994 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow Russian Television Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By correspondent A. Yaroshevskiy; from the "Vesti" newscast] </F>
  [Text] Today the leaders of all groups in the lower chamber 
of the Russian Parliament and its chairmen sent a letter to 
Boris Yeltsin containing a warning, to the effect that the 
Russo-Georgian friendship treaty may not be ratified by the 
State Duma. The main reason for apprehension is a possible 
destabilization of the situation in the Caucasus, associated 
with signing the treaty. 
  [Yaroshevskiy] Konstantin Zatulin, chairman of the State 
Duma's Committee for CIS Affairs and Links With Compatriots, has 
just ended a news conference, at which he acquainted journalists 
with the committee's statement on the Russo-Georgian treaty. 
Essentially the first serious non-acceptance of a presidential 
decision by Duma deputies was occasioned mainly by worries about 
exacerbating the conflicts in the Caucasus and the siting of 
Russian military bases in Georgia. 
  Incidentally, Zatulin acknowledged that some information on 
the subject leaked from the mass media, specifically from 
Russian TV's political observer Nikolay Svanidze, yesterday. 
Evidently, in a week's time, on Thursday, the State Duma will 
debate Russo-Georgian relations, whatever the outcome of the 
talks between Yeltsin and Shevardnadze. 
  [Zatulin] The State Duma cannot, has no right, and I think 
from a moral and ethical point of view, ought not to instruct 
the president of the Russian Federation as to where he goes or 
when. 

</TEXT>

