<F P=100> Regional Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   North Ossetia Situation Reportedly Stabilizing </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0402135794 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1229 GMT 4 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0402135794 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Valeriy Shanayev] </F>
  [Text] Vladikavkaz February 4 TASS -- The situation in 
North Ossetia, where the state of emergency has been prolonged 
by Russian President Boris Yeltsin's decree for another two 
months, is stabilizing. 
  According to military sources, no clashes on ethnic grounds 
have been reported in more than 24 hours. Russia's peace 
keepers jointly with local law enforcement agencies are 
maintaining the state of emergency. 
  North Ossetian Parliament Chairman Yuriy Biragov today 
presided over a session of the republic's commission on 
restructuring the bodies of state authority and local government 
in line with the Russian president's decree. 
  Commission members discussed reforms in the republic, the 
structure of the future parliament and elections to local self 
government agencies. Its proposals will be submitted to the 
republic's parliament for consideration. 

</TEXT>

