<F P=100> Regional Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Galazov Assesses Round of Talks </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0602151594 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1445 GMT 6 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0602151594 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Valeriy Shanayev] </F>
  [Text] Vladikavkaz February 6 TASS--North Ossetia's first 
President Akhsarbek Galazov assessed the past week as intense 
and fruitful. "Taking part in the work of the Russian 
parliament's upper house, I managed to meet with Russian head of 
government Viktor Chernomyrdin and other leaders of the Russian 
Federation", Galazov told TASS on returning from Moscow. "We 
considered some pressing issues aiming to assist the republic in 
solving social and economic problems", he reported. 
  Commenting on the meeting of the Russian Government 
presidium, which discussed the situation in the zone under state 
of emergency rule in the light of the presidential decree 
extending the state of emergency for another two months, the 
North Ossetian president said "the Russian president's decree 
was been approved but with considerable reservations. A 
deputies' group was set up to gather objective information on 
the spot... I submitted to the Russian Government our proposals 
as for how achieve a peaceful settlement in relations between 
North Ossetia and Ingushetia. These proposals had been approved 
by the republic's multi-national people. The Ossetian side is 
ready to work for improving relations with all neighbouring 
countries. But we must not use force on this way towards peace. 
Force engenders only force", Galazov stressed. 
  The North Ossetian leader flatly rejected the idea by the 
Ingush side of imposing a special rule on the Prigorodniy 
District as the sole possible way to overcome the current 
crisis. Galazov qualified the idea as a gross interference into 
North Ossetia's internal affairs. "The problem of refugees' 
return should be solved not with military help of federal 
authorities, but on the basis of Kislovodsk accords", he said 
referring to the agreements on a complex solution to the problem 
of refugees and forced migrants in Ingushetia and North Ossetia, 
which were reached by the Russian, Ingush and North Ossetian 
delegations in the North Caucasian town of Kislovodsk last 
March. "Of the greatest importance here are conciliation 
commissions now working in each locality of the Prigorodniy 
District", Galazov emphasised. 
  The situation in the zone under state of emergency rule, 
which has been extended for another two months, remains 
relatively calm, TASS was told at the North Ossetian Security 
Council. Military sources confirmed that no conflicts on ethnic 
grounds had been registered there. Russian peacekeeping forces 
and local law-enforcement bodies are in control of the situation. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

