<F P=100> Regional Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Karelia Suffering Critical Fuel Shortages </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0502155094 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1421 GMT 5 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0502155094 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] The Russian republic of Karelia is desperately short 
of fuel, according to an officer at the republic's civil defense 
headquarters. 
  The officer told INTERFAX the stocks of residual fuel oil in 
the republic's capital Petrozavodsk and in Medvezhyegorsk would 
only last three days, those in Belomorsk and Segezh for two 
days. Coal supplies in Petrozavodsk would run out in a week, 
those in Medvezhyegorsk in four days, he said. 
  Karelia is unable to pay the firms providing it with fuel 
and 
has asked the federal government for help, the officer said. A 
commission has been set up in the republic to redistribute the 
remaining fuel to keep the central heating systems and larger 
factories going. 
  According to some sources, the Karelian government was due 
to 
meet on Saturday to discuss emergency measures. 
  The temperature in the republic, which lies in northwestern 
Russia, has these days been staying at between minus 18 and 20 
degrees Centigrade. 

</TEXT>

