<F P=100> Regional Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Energy Minister Addresses Khabarovsk Fuel Shortage </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0702092594 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 0811 GMT 7 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0702092594 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Leonid Vinogradov] </F>
  [Text] Vladivostok February 7 TASS -- Russia's Far East is 
suffering from the cold and this suffering is further aggravated 
by the disruption of fuel and energy supplies. The Federal Fuel 
and Energy Minister Yuriy Shafranik has had to fly to Khabarovsk 
in order to try and solve the most pressing problems "on site". 
  According to specialists, all enterprises in this vast 
region 
are likely to stop unless emergency measures are taken promptly. 
The cities will have to live without electricity for ten hours 
every day, and the local thermal power stations will use up all 
the electricity to keep going. 
  The Russian Maritime Territory needs about 47,000 tonnes of 
coal every day to keep its electricity-generating plants going. 
At present, the daily supplies have dwindled to 23-25 thousand 
tonnes, and the emergency reserves are vanishing. This is why 
electricity supplies have to be cut off in the evenings and the 
major cities, including Vladivostok, Nakhodka, Ussuriisk and 
others are plunged in the shadows one after another in the 
evenings. In many houses and departments the average 
temperature never rises about 6-7 degrees centigrade. 
  The energy crisis is largely due to the epidemic of 
non-payment, although the federal government adopted a 
resolution on October 8, 1993 to bring about "emergency measures 
of support of the Maritime Territory". The federal budget owes 
more than 30 billion roubles to the coal producers. The 
coalminers in the territory are owed 19 billion roubles in wages. 
  Last year the Primorugol Association was unable to purchase 
a 
single mechanised set of machinery. The machinery and equipment 
now used by the miners are wornout and even at full capacity 
produce a million tonnes of coal less than planned. 
  The federal government delivered 35 billion roubles to the 
territory but the money was fully spent to pay for earlier 
supplies. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-36392 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drsov025_d_94011" </HT>


