<F P=100> Regional Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   `Economic Union' of Far East Regions Formed </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0702073894 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 0733 GMT 7 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0702073894 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Eduard Popov] </F>
  [Text] Vladivostok February 7 TASS -- Seven northern 
regions of Russia's far eastern Maritime Territory have joined 
in an economic union, which "has nothing to do with separatism," 
according to deputy administration chief of the Maritime 
Territory Fedor Konyukhov. 
  "The commonality of the geographic location and economic 
problems necessitate the consolidation of efforts in the 
interests of the entire territory. The most pressing task is to 
revivify the timber, mining and fur industries and to combat the 
plunder of natural riches and their illicit export," Konyukhov 
said. 
  According to Konyukhov, the new organisation will form an 
economic mini-community within this component part of the 
Russian Federation. It pursues no political aims. 
  Work is under way on the charter and programme of the 
economic union which are expected to be approved by the second 
joint session of the heads of administrations. The organisation 
will be funded from the budget of the territory and its 
component parts. 

</TEXT>

