<F P=100> UKRAINE </F>
<F P=101> International Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Navy Spokesman Denies Incident </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0502221994 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1658 GMT 5 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0502221994 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] A Ukrainian Navy spokesman has denied statements by 
senior officers in the Black Sea Fleet (BSF) that Ukrainian 
servicemen tried to seize a BSF hospital base on Friday. 
  Nikolay Savchenko, head of the Ukrainian Navy press center, 
said the BSF command ordered the removal of all property from 
the storehouses of a hospital base at Nikolayev after the 
officers serving at it applied to join the Ukrainian Navy, 
"having lost any hope that a civilized solution will be found to 
the problem of the Black Sea Fleet." 
  Savchenko said the BSF command was obeying only the orders 
and instructions of the Russian Defense Ministry, though the 
hospital base officers and employees were Ukrainian citizens. 
  "The uncontrolled removal of property from bases situated on 
Ukrainian territory does not help to find a civilized solution 
to the problem of the Black Sea Fleet," Savchenko said. 
  BSF spokesman Andrey Grachev told Interfax on Friday that 
more than 300 Ukrainian military officers, 10 of them armed with 
submachineguns, had burst into the base after officers serving 
at it applied to join the Ukrainian Navy. 

</TEXT>

