<F P=100> UKRAINE </F>
<F P=101> International Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Zlenko Explains Parliament's Decision on START </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0402155194 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1411 GMT 4 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0402155194 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Having removed the reservations to Article 5 of the 
Lisbon protocol to the START-1 treaty, the Ukrainian Parliament 
has confirmed Ukraine's intention to join shortly the nuclear 
Non-Proliferation Treaty as a non-nuclear country. This 
statement was made by Ukrainian Foreign Minister Anatoliy Zlenko 
in Kiev Friday at the meeting with diplomats and journalists. 
  He has said that the absence of the decision on joining the 
treaty should not be interpreted as a negative attitude to the 
document. The issue is still on the agenda, believes the 
Ukrainian Foreign Minister. 
  The parliament resolution, said the Minister, opens the way 
to the implementation of tripartite documents on nuclear 
disarmament, involving Ukraine, the United States and Russia. 
Zlenko believes that it is planned to hold shortly bilateral 
and tripartite talks of experts on the implementation of the 
Moscow documents. He said that the date for the talks is about 
to be set. 
  Zlenko believes the parliament resolution will provide the 
possibility to boost the negotiations with international 
financial organizations to offer Ukraine effective economic aid. 
The Minister also pointed to the need to speed up the financial 
and economic aid to Ukraine. 
  "I am absolutely sure," he said, "that the treaty should not 
be an obstacle to providing aid to Ukraine," said Zlenko. 
  The wording of the resolution's second provision 
unambiguously points to the fact that the exchange of the 
instruments of ratification on the START-1 treaty will be the 
first step. At the same time, he said, the parties involved 
will negotiate concrete intergovernment agreements which proceed 
from the reservations contained in the parliament resolution of 
November 18, 1993. 
  Asked by Interfax-Ukraine about possible debates in 
parliament over the timetable for Ukraine joining the treaty, 
Zlenko did not rule out that the present parliament would also 
consider the issue. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

