<DOCNO> FBIS3-36400 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drsov025_e_94009" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-SOV-94-025 </AU>
Document Type:Daily Report 
<DATE1>  7 Feb 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> UKRAINE </F>
<F P=101> International Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Praises Removal of Article 5 Reservations </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  WS0402163494 Kiev Ukrayinske Radio First Program Network in 
Ukrainian 1500 GMT 4 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> WS0402163494 </F>
<F P=104>  Kiev Ukrayinske Radio First Program Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Ukrainian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Ukrainian Foreign Minister Anatoliy Zlenko deemed 
the adoption by the Ukrainian Supreme Council of a resolution on 
withdrawing reservations to Article 5 of the Lisbon Protocol to 
be an important event. Speaking at a news conference held at 
the Ukrainian Foreign Ministry today, the minister emphasized 
that an important fact about this resolution is that the Supreme 
Council positively evaluated steps taken by the Ukrainian 
president and Government directed at implementing 
recommendations suggested by the Ukrainian parliament, which was 
reflected in the tripartite declaration and a supplement to it. 
It should be stressed, Anatoliy Zlenko noted, that by taking 
back its reservations to Article 5 of the Lisbon Protocol, the 
Ukrainian Supreme Council reconfirmed Ukraine's intention to 
join the nuclear Nonproliferation Treaty as a non-nuclear state. 
He also explained that the fact that the resolution did not 
contain a decision to join the Nonproliferation Treaty should 
not be understood as the legislature's negative attitude toward 
the treaty in principle, but as its intention to examine this 
issue at a separate session. This proves, Anatoliy Zlenko said, 
that the issue of joining the treaty has not been taken off the 
agenda. 

</TEXT>

