<F P=100> UKRAINE </F>
<F P=101> International Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Defense Minister Warns on Danger of Old Warheads </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  MK0402131094 Moscow SEGODNYA in Russian 4 Feb 94 p 1 </F>
<F P=103> MK0402131094 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow SEGODNYA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Konstantin Parishkura report from Kiev under the "SALT" </F>
rubric: "Ukrainian Parliament Concerned Over Compensation for 
Nuclear Bomb. Defense Minister Warns About Possible Catastrophe"] 
  [Text] Yesterday the Ukrainian Supreme Council tasked the 
Council of Ministers with "stepping up efforts" to sign specific 
treaties on compensation for the nuclear weapons to be removed 
from Ukraine. As for Ukraine's accession to the Nuclear 
Nonproliferation Treaty, it was decided to consider the question 
at a separate Supreme Council meeting. Foreign Minister 
Anatoliy Zlenko said that "Ukraine has considerably tarnished 
its image as an international partner by reneging on its 
promises." Defense Minister Vitaliy Radetskiy sweetened the 
pill by saying that Ukraine is a powerful space state that will 
in time be capable of manufacturing delivery vehicles and 
weapons on its own. But later he said that the storage time of 
the combat nuclear blocs, where uncontrollable physical 
processes may begin, is drawing to an end and that "the 
Chernobyl catastrophe would pale beside what might happen." 
  Mr. Kravchuk, on his part, said that he received a telegram 
from U.S. President Clinton on 3 February saying that the United 
States plans to double its aid for dismantling nuclear weapons 
in Ukraine. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

