<F P=101> International Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   CSCE Delegation Leader Views Russian Foreign Policy </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0502145394 Kiev Radio Ukraine World Service in Ukrainian 
0600 GMT 5 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0502145394 </F>
<F P=104>  Kiev Radio Ukraine World Service </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Ukrainian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] At the latest plenary session in Vienna of the 
permanent committee of the Conference on Security and 
Cooperation in Europe [CSCE] Yuriy Kostenko, the head of 
Ukraine's delegation, commented on a statement by Russian 
Foreign Minister Andrey Kozyrev. 
  In his speech Yuriy Kostenko especially drew the attention 
of 
the representatives from CSCE member states to Ukraine's deep 
concern that a tendency has recently been discerned in Russia's 
policy toward increasing the toughness of its foreign policy 
course, in particular toward the independent states created 
after the break-up of the USSR. 
  Notwithstanding the statements on the main new threat to 
international peace and security, which Russia describes as 
aggressive nationalism, the Ukrainian representative continued, 
whether it wants to or not Russia is provoking the exacerbation 
of this issue and thus is inciting the citizens of Russian 
descent in other states to expressions of national intolerance. 
  The speech by the head of Ukraine's delegation was 
positively 
evaluated by the delegation from the United States, which 
interpreted it as an attempt at an early stage to facilitate the 
prevention of conflicts emerging on an interethnic basis, in 
particular in the Crimea. 

</TEXT>

