<H3> <TI>   Meshkov Addresses Crimean People; To Visit Moscow </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0402160494 Moscow Radio Rossii Network in Russian 1100 GMT 
4 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0402160494 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow Radio Rossii Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Yuriy Meshkov, the first president of the Crimean 
peninsula, was sworn in today. Let us recall one interesting 
aspect of his career. As a student at the law faculty of Moscow 
State University, Meshkov wrote his thesis under the supervision 
of Professor [Valeriy] Zorkin. Correspondent Yevgeniy Novikov 
reports on how the inauguration of the Crimean president went: 
  [Begin Novikov recording] The session was opened by Ivan 
Yermakov, deputy chairman of the Supreme Soviet. He asked 
Meshkov to come to the rostrum for his official inauguration as 
president. Meshkov pledged allegiance to the people of the 
Crimea and solemnly swore to abide by the Constitution and laws 
of the Republic of the Crimea. After the inauguration ceremony, 
Yermakov read out congratulatory telegrams to the Crimean 
president. Telegrams were received from Belarusian Supreme 
Soviet Chairman Myechyslaw Gryb, from Yegor Gaydar, Grigoriy 
Yavlinskiy, Vladimir Shumeyko, Konstantin Zatulin, the 
presidents of the autonomous republics of the Russian 
Federation, and from Eduard Baltin, commander in chief of the 
Black Sea Fleet. 
  Meshkov delivered an address to the citizens of the Republic 
of Crimea. He assured Crimeans that he would work for the 
further development of Crimea's statehood. Meshkov also 
disclosed that he intended to fly to Kiev immediately in order 
to meet Leonid Kravchuk. After meeting the Ukrainian president, 
Meshkov will go on to Moscow. 
  A recess in the session was declared after Meshkov's speech. 
During the recess, Igor Yezarov, the Crimean president's press 
secretary, held a news conference for Crimean and foreign 
correspondents. Among other things, Yezarov disclosed that 
Meshkov had prepared a number of important decrees, including a 
decree on relay of all Radio Russia and Russian television 
programs to the Crimea. [end recording] 

</TEXT>

