<F P=100> National Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Crimean Deputies Reach No Conclusions on Referendum </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0502162094 Kiev UNIAN in Ukrainian 0930 GMT 5 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0502162094 </F>
<F P=104>  Kiev UNIAN </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Ukrainian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Simferopol -- After Crimean President Yuriy Meshkov 
left on a flight for Kiev on 4 February, Crimean 
parliamentarians again raised the issue of canceling the 
moratorium on the referendum on the status of the Crimea, but 
yet again it was not even included on the session's agenda. The 
same fate befell the proposal of Deputy Vadim Kolesnichenko, who 
proposed that Yuriy Meshkov be granted the appropriate powers to 
carry out his election promises (entry into the ruble zone, dual 
citizenship, payment of pensions in karbovantsi, and so on). 
  A debate only developed during the examination of the 
resignation statement of Nikolay Bagrov, chairman of the Crimean 
Supreme Council. His resignation was not accepted. It was 
decided to examine this issue only after Nikolay Bagrov returns 
from his vacation, which he took when he lost the struggle with 
Yuriy Meshkov for the presidential seat. 

</TEXT>

