<F P=100> Moldova </F>
<H3> <TI>   Snegur Signs Decree on Independence Referendum </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0402223794 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1950 GMT 4 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0402223794 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Moldovan President Mircea Snegur signed a decree 
saying that a referendum on confirmation of the republic's 
independence be held with the participation of all Moldova's 
inhabitants on Friday. The referendum is to take place on March 
6. 
  Voters will be required to answer a single question: "Do you 
support that the Republic of Moldova develop as an independent 
and integral state within the borders recognized by the UN, 
pursue the policy of neutrality and maintain mutually beneficial 
economic relations with any state and that equal human rights be 
guaranteed to all citizens in accordance with principles of 
international law?" 
  The Central Election Commission on parliamentary elections 
rejected the president's proposal that the referendum be held 
together with the parliamentary elections on February 27. 
However, the president acted in conformity with the current 
legislature and assumed the responsibility for holding of the 
sociological poll. 
  According to observers in Kishinev, the Moldovan president's 
decision on the referendum was aimed at discouraging those who 
support the idea of unification between Moldova and Romania. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

