<DOCNO> FBIS3-36427 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drsov025_h_94002" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-SOV-94-025 </AU>
Document Type:Daily Report 
<DATE1>  7 Feb 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> Moldova </F>
<H3> <TI>   Decree on 6 Mar Poll </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU0502135194 Bucharest Radio Romania Network in Romanian 
2000 GMT 4 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> AU0502135194 </F>
<F P=104>  Bucharest Radio Romania Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Romanian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Anca Florea report from Chisinau] </F>
  [Text] This evening Radio Chisinau broadcast the decree 
issued by President Mircea Snegur regarding the sociological 
poll titled "Consulting With the Nation" [La Sfat Cu Poporul]. 
  Taking note of the Central Electoral Commission's decision 
of 
2 February, which practically rejects President Snegur's 
proposal that according to the decision of the presidium of the 
Parliament of the Republic of Moldova the aforementioned poll 
should be organized simultaneously with the 27 February general 
elections, but, on the other hand, considering the stringent 
need to stabilize the social, political, and economic situation 
in the country, to create favorable circumstances for the 
strengthening of the independence of the Republic of Moldova and 
the ensuring of its territorial integrity, and on the basis of 
Article 113 of the Constitution of the Republic of Moldova, the 
president of the republic decrees, I quote the first article: 
  On 6 March 1994 the sociological poll "Consulting With the 
Nation" is to be held on the whole territory of the Republic of 
Moldova. The poll is intended for all citizens of the republic 
with the right to vote to answer the following question: Do you 
favor the Republic of Moldova to develop as an independent, 
unitary, and indivisible state, within its frontiers established 
on the day of the proclamation of its sovereignty, 23 June 1990, 
to promote a neutral policy, to maintain mutually advantageous 
cooperation relations with all the countries of the world, and 
to guarantee equal rights to all its citizens, according to the 
norms of the international right? unquote. 
  The five articles that follow the first one regulate the way 
in which the poll is to be prepared. 
  Also today the Central Electoral Commission held a news 
conference, during which the journalists were told that 1,024 
candidates representing 16 political groupings and 19 
independent candidates have registered for the 27 February 
ballot. The commission members also said that 44 technical 
groups [for ballot counting] have been set up and the voting 
bulletins have also been confirmed. 
  The commission members also emphasized that although they 
had 
done everything they could to organize elections also on the 
left bank of the Dniester River [in the self-proclaimed Dniester 
Republic], as well as in the southern part of the republic 
[inhabited by the Gagauz ethnic minority], for the time being it 
is still unclear whether the elections will also take place in 
those regions. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

