<F P=100> Kyrgyzstan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Akayev Establishes Security Council </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0402211694 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1930 GMT 4 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0402211694 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "Presidential Bulletin"] </F>
  [Text] President Askar Akayev on Thursday formed a security 
council to coordinate activities carried out by appropriate 
agencies in the field. 
  This advisory board, as the presidential decree notes, is 
assigned to draft presidential decisions on republican security, 
plan anti-crime campaigns, consult the president on the 
republican health service, forecast and prevent emergencies and 
eliminate their effects, and advise the president on everything 
that concerns a state of emergency, including its imposition, 
extension, and repeal. 
  The council comprises the prime minister, chairman of the 
commission for emergencies in the rank of deputy premier, power 
ministers, national guards commander, presidential 
administration chief, and president's national security adviser. 
The board, which will meet once a month, can invite the 
Parliament's Speaker and other persons. 
  Conferring with the power ministers on Thursday, Akayev 
pointed to shortcomings in the fight against crime and said that 
after the credit of trust from the voters he would spare no 
effort to restore order in the republic. He gave instructions 
on drafting decrees to this effect. 
  Akayev also had a closed meeting with the finance minister, 
taxation and custom service chiefs, and other officials to 
discuss ways of collecting taxes and securing finances. It was 
noted that sizable revenues were lost because many enterprises 
had been evading taxes. For this reason, Akayev threatened to 
deal ruthlessly with tax evaders, whose actions, as he put it, 
"undermine the security of the entire state." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

