<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Split Occurs Within PRAVDA's Staff </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0502154994 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1343 GMT 5 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0502154994 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] "A disgraceful page has been written into the 
history of the oldest paper in the country," said the editor of 
PRAVDA, Viktor Linnik. 
  He told a news conference in Moscow on Friday that the same 
day part of the newspaper's staff had decided to continue 
cooperation with the Greek company Stilight Holdings Ltd., fire 
Linnik and replace him with acting editor Aleksandr Ilyin. 
  Linnik said the majority of the staff did not recognize the 
decision, since most of those present at the meeting where it 
was taken were members of the Greek company. 
  He said only 76 people of PRAVDA's staff of 233 had attended 
the meeting. "One may say a split has occurred within our 
staff," he said. 
  Linnik said Stilight Holdings insisted that all rights to 
the 
newspaper be handed over to PRAVDA International, where the 
Greek company holds the controlling interest, 55 percent of 
shares. But the editorial board and most of the staff of PRAVDA 
wished the controlling interest in the paper to be owned by a 
Russian corporation, he said. 
  Linnik said PRAVDA had already started talks to that end 
with 
one of the financial groups. As the first step, the PRAVDA 
staff, late in December, decided to make the paper a 
public-stock company called the PRAVDA Concern. 
  He said Stilight Holdings had been dissatisfied with it, 
appealing to court against the decision of the PRAVDA staff to 
reregister the paper and organizing Friday's staff meeting. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

