<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Chemist Mirzayanov's Trial May Be Dismissed </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  MK0502094094 Moscow NEZAVISIMAYA GAZETA in Russian 5 Feb 94 
p 1 </F>

<F P=103> MK0502094094 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow NEZAVISIMAYA GAZETA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed report under the "In Brief" rubric: </F>
"`Mirzayanov Case' To Be Dismissed"] 
  [Text] The trial of chemist Vil Mirzayanov will likely be 
dismissed in the coming days. According to some information, 
Yuriy Baturin, the Russian president's national security 
adviser, has reported in detail to Boris Yeltsin the 
circumstances of the criminal case against the scientist who had 
allegedly revealed a state secret about the development in 
Russia of new types of chemical weapons, and the president 
"adequately reacted to the prosecution's being 
unconstitutional." Yuriy Baturin explained that a criminal case 
under Article 6 of the Criminal Procedure Code may be dismissed 
in connection with changed circumstances. He regards as such 
"changed circumstances" the adoption of the new Russian 
Federation Constitution under which "everyone has the right to 
freely look for, receive, pass on, produce, and distribute 
information by any legal means. The list of information 
constituting a state secret is determined by a federal law." 
Since no open list of information about state secrets has been 
published, this circumstance may be cause for dismissing the 
case against the scientist, something Russian human rights 
activists and the liberal press insist on. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

