<H3> <TI>   Yeltsin Opposed to Trial </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0402151894 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 1409 
GMT 4 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0402151894 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Igor Belskiy] </F>
  [Text] Moscow, 4 Feb--Chemist Vil Mirzayanov, who is 
accused of divulging state secrets, began to testify in court 
today, Mirzayanov's lawyer Aleksandre Asnis told journalists 
during a break in the court session. He informed journalists 
and lawyers that the court had dismissed his client's appeal for 
a mistrial and for the trial to be make public. In the lawyer's 
words, the court questioned witness Nikishin, after which the 
defendant "considered it possible for him to answer questions 
from participants in the trial". 
  At the same time, ITAR-TASS has learned from sources close 
to 
the Russian president that Boris Yeltsin tends to believe that 
the trial of the scientist is unconstitutional, and he may soon 
use his influence as guarantor of the Constitution to stop the 
Mirzayanov trial. 

</TEXT>

