<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Mirzayanov Not To Appeal for Release </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0402220794 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1950 GMT 4 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0402220794 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Russian scientist Vil Mirzayanov, charged with 
divulging a national secret, does not wish to appeal for release 
from custody, his counsel for the defense said. 
  The counsel, Aleksandr Asnis, told Interfax on Friday the 
scientist had even refused to discuss the matter with him. 
  Asnis said the Moscow City Court had continued questioning 
Mirzayanov on Friday afternoon. The scientist "agreed to give 
evidence because he still hoped to make it clear to the judges 
why he does not consider himself to be guilty," Asnis said. 
  He said he hoped the interrogation of Mirzayanov and 
witnesses would persuade the counsel for the prosecution, Leonid 
Pankratov, to ask for an additional investigation of the case. 
  Mirzayanov's interrogation will be continued at the next 
court session at 10:30 on February 7. 
  The prosecution against Mirzayanov was started in 1992, 
after 
the newspaper Moscow News carried his story "Poisoned Policy," 
which said Russia was creating binary weapons. 

</TEXT>

