<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Scientist Will Not Reveal Chemical Weapons Secrets </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0402214394 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1950 GMT 4 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0402214394 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] The former senior analyst of one of the secret 
research institutes, Vladimir Uglyov, told a press conference in 
Moscow today that he will not inform Russian and foreign 
journalists of new chemical weapons developed in Russia. Uglyov 
had announced his attention to reveal this information in his 
address to Russian President Boris Yeltsin on January 22, if the 
latter failed to discuss with him issues related to the 
destruction of chemical weapons. 
  The chemist explained his decision by the fact that he saw 
hope that the authorities could hear his voice after his recent 
meeting with the presidential advisor for national security, 
Yuriy Baturin. In addition, Uglyov said he feared that revealing 
the formula and other specific features of the new chemical 
weapons could enable some countries to launch its uncontrolled 
production. 
  Uglyov also said he held hope for a favorable end of 
"Mirzayanov's fanned case." He said the scientist's intention 
to reveal the formula was the reason for launching legal 
proceedings against him. 
  The press conference was also attended by another former 
chemist, now disabled Vladimir Petrenko, who became victim of 
chemical weapons tests conducted in the institute over a decade 
ago. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

