<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Economic Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Gerashchenko: State Must Pay Debts </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0402205294 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1908 GMT 4 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0402205294 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS parliamentary correspondent Ivan Novikov for </F>
TASS] 
  [Text] Moscow February 4 TASS -- "The state must pay its 
debts," Viktor Gerashchenko, chairman of Russia's Central Bank, 
said on Friday, addressing the lower house of the Russian 
parliament on an item entitled "an hour of the government." 
  Gerashchenko declared that the outstanding debts of the 
state 
to some sectors of the economy, and farmers, in particular, 
would be paid, although not simultaneously. Gerashchenko said 
that the total debt amounts to almost eight trillions roubles. 
Chairman of Russia's Central Bank pointed out that the question 
of outstanding debts was discussed at a session of the Russian 
Government on Thursday, adding that the matter would be 
finalized during next week and afterwards, positively resolved. 
  Russian lawmakers found it a paradox to hear Gerashchenko 
say 
that currently, the system of mutual payments has been working 
better than before, including with former Soviet republics. 
Gerashchenko pointed out that there is an active balance of 
payments between Russia and CIS countries. "We are pursuing a 
policy of restricting credits issued to CIS countries from the 
state budget," Gerashchenko said. 
  Asked where Russia will find money to grant a credit to 
Georgia, Gerashchenko replied that "our leaders can prove to the 
State Duma that such a credit is necessary." 
  Commenting on the current financial situation in Russia, 
Gerashchenko said that "we have been going up the spiral of 
inflation all the time." He admitted that the Central Bank 
spent over a million dollars in January alone to stabilise the 
rouble exchange rate. 
  Gerashchenko pointed out that according to estimates made by 
the Central Bank, last year, the budget deficit was within 10.5 
per cent of the gross national product. But in his opinion, "no 
tragedy has occurred." 
  Gerashchenko declared that currently, "we have been 
constantly experimenting which might trigger inflation to a 
certain degree and perhaps, we shall not attain the reduction of 
the budget deficit by 5 per cent of the size of the gross 
national product as we would like to do." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-36457 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drsov025_b_94021" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-SOV-94-025 </AU>
Document Type:Daily Report 
<DATE1>  7 Feb 1994 </DATE1>

