<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Military &amp; Space Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Defense Minister Says Army of 2 Million Needed </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0402154594 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 1423 
GMT 4 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0402154594 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Mikhail Shevtsov] </F>
  [Text] Moscow, 4 Jan--"A Russian Army capable of carrying 
out all of the tasks allotted to it should number 2-2.1 
million," the Russian defense minister stated at a meeting in 
Georgia with officers from the 405th Motorized Infantry Regiment 
stationed in Vaziani. In his opinion, numbers for the Armed 
Forces as set out in the defense law--1.5 million by 1995--are 
insufficient to carry out the tasks of guaranteeing the state's 
security. 
  Pavel Grachev confirmed the military department's policy of 
recruitment on contract. Contract soldiers, the minister said, 
will be recruited mainly for the fighting units and not for the 
administrative or quartermasters' services. In 1993, 93,000 
contract soldiers were recruited in 1993. The plan is to 
recruit 150,000-160,000 contract soldiers in 1994. 
  The defense minister also spoke of the proposed 
reorganization of educational work in the Army. Its focus will 
move from the center to the level of companies, battalions, and 
regiments. There are specific proposals for regiments to have a 
deputy commander responsible for educational work, a lawyer, 
psychologist, and a sociologist. 

</TEXT>

