<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Military &amp; Space Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Army's Control of Weapons Criticized </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0402161694 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1357 GMT 4 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0402161694 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Vladimir Gondusov] </F>
  [Text] Moscow February 4 TASS--A captain in the Russian 
Army is one of two men, detained by detectives from the 
Khabarovsk Territorial Internal Affairs Department on the 
suspicion that they stole 75 guns. Several of the weapons were 
discovered with the suspects, while the rest have yet to be 
found, according to the Public Communications Center of the 
Russian Ministry of Internal Affairs. 
  Specialists in the Interior Ministry still consider Army 
units a stable "source of supply" of weapons to criminal 
elements. Military personnel fairly often make off with guns 
and ammunition in order to earn some extra money. In 1993, 6430 
weapons were illegally "transferred" into criminal hands, twice 
as much as the corresponding 1992 figure. Every third stolen 
weapon is from the Army. 
  Deputy Chief of the law and order department's investigative 
section Leonid Turchin says he is "astonished" by the fact that 
unit and regiment commanders cannot ensure the safekeeping of 
weapons and explosives, even when they are locked up in depots, 
located in military bases and surrounded by high fences and 
barbed wire. 

</TEXT>

