<F P=100> Latvia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Foreign Minister Favors Russian Plan for Skrunda </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  MK0502143094 Moscow NEZAVISIMAYA GAZETA in Russian 5 Feb 94 
p 3 </F>

<F P=103> MK0502143094 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow NEZAVISIMAYA GAZETA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed report in the "In Brief" column] </F>
  [Text] Latvia's Foreign Affairs Minister Georg Andreyev 
said that the Latvian delegation to the talks with Russia should 
agree to the plan which will probably be proposed by the Russian 
side in the course of the next round. 
  Russia's intention to seek compromise, which came as a 
result 
of a meeting in Moscow between Russian Government 
representatives, U.S. President Bill Clinton, and the Latvian 
delegation led by Andreyev, was announced in Washington by U.S. 
Administration officials. Under the new plan, the radar station 
in Skrunda will operate for another four years and will then be 
dismantled within 18 months. 
  At present, however, Russia's position adopted during the 
previous round is still valid at the current Latvian-Russian 
intergovernment negotiations, whereby the operation of the 
Skrunda radar will be extended for five years. Officially 
Russia has not as yet advised Latvia about a change of position. 
  According to Andreyev, it is still not clear how this issue 
will be decided. The Latvian delegation's mandate may be 
changed only after this issue has been studied by the 
leadership, for example, the Saeima's Interfactional Council. 
The minister said that to prevent an indefinite delay in its 
resolution, this question should not be discussed at a plenary 
Saeima session. 

</TEXT>

