<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Grachev Briefs Leotard on Serbia </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0402133594 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1151 GMT 4 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0402133594 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Russia's Defense Minister Pavel Grachev has warned 
against bombing Serbian positions in Bosnia. Such a strike, in 
his opinion, could be delivered only if Serbian troops engage 
the peacekeepers. According to Grachev, Russia's position is 
that a decision on a bombing raid should only be made by the UN 
Security Council rather than by the peacekeeping forces' command. 
  He outlined this position at his meeting with his French 
counterpart Francois Leotard in Moscow on Friday. 
  Commenting on the conflict in former Yugoslavia, Grachev 
said 
that to secure a cease-fire in Bosnia, Russia would press for 
"equally restraining" not only the Bosnian Serbs but also the 
Croatian and Moslem communities. 
  Explaining his government's position on a settlement in 
Bosnia, Grachev urged the conflicting sides to call a 
cease-fire, ensure the passage of humanitarian relief convoys, 
and guarantee security in the region. 

</TEXT>

