<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Foreign Minister Kozyrev Comments on Russo-Georgian Treaty </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0402120694 Tbilisi Radio Tbilisi Network in Russian 0900 
GMT 4 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0402120694 </F>
<F P=104>  Tbilisi Radio Tbilisi Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Interview with Russian Foreign Minister Andrey Kozyrev by </F>
unidentified correspondent; place and date not given--recorded] 
  [Text] [Kozyrev] We view the signing of the 
[Russo-Georgian] treaty as an incentive for further efforts to 
regulate the conflicts that are worrying us in Abkhazia and 
South Ossetia and for securing the human rights of national 
minorities. The treaty will come into full force only after 
this is done. The treaty will be ratified but, for the time 
being, it is important that the treaty serve as an incentive on 
these issues and not a substitute. 
  [Correspondent] In Sochi you declared that Russia had legal, 
historical, and strategic interests in the Transcaucasus. How 
will these interests reflect on the Abkhaz issue? 
  [Kozyrev] This issue should be regulated in such a way that 
would allow Georgian integrity. At the same time, the status of 
Abkhazia will be defined so that peace is established in Georgia. 
  [Correspondent] How can that be done? 
  [Kozyrev] It is an issue for negotiation. 

</TEXT>

