<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Shakhray `Objects' To Wording </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0502200894 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1658 GMT 5 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0502200894 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Though finding it necessary to sign a treaty between 
Russia and Georgia, the Minister for Ethnic and Regional 
Policies, Sergey Shakhray, objects to the wording of the treaty. 
  Addressing journalists in Moscow on Saturday, he said: To 
preserve Georgia's territorial integrity, as a condition for 
stability in the region, and ensure the status of autonomy for 
Abkhazia, South Ossetia and Ajaria, would answer to Russia's 
strategic interests. 
  "In my view, the ideal model for Georgia would be federal 
system," Shakhray said. "There is no other way to preserve 
Georgia's territorial integrity and stop the civil war and 
ethnic conflicts there." 
  According to him, there should have been a preliminary 
condition for signing the bilateral treaty: the understanding 
that Russia will act as the guarantor of the autonomous status 
of republics within Georgia, without interfering in Georgia's 
internal affairs. 
  Since this has not been stipulated, the treaty may become a 
pretext for destabilizing the situation even before its 
ratification, Shakhray said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-36504 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drsov025_a_94030" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-SOV-94-025 </AU>
Document Type:Daily Report 
<DATE1>  7 Feb 1994 </DATE1>

