<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Government May Allocate 20 Billion Ruble Credit To Georgia </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0402205494 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1954 GMT 4 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0402205494 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Oleg Velichko] </F>
  [Text] Moscow February 4 TASS -- First Deputy Chairman of 
the Russian Government, Oleg Soskovets, described documents on 
cooperation signed by Russia and Georgia to be extremely 
important, saying that the two countries took into account new 
political realities which were formed after the disintegration 
of the former Soviet Union and legalised earlier established 
economic ties. 
  Addressing a meeting with journalists which was held at the 
government building on the Krasnopresnenskaya Embankment on 
Friday [4 February], Soskovets focused on the Russo-Georgian 
package of trade and economic agreements. Soskovets is deeply 
convinced that both countries seek to find a common approach to 
the development of industrial infrastructure. 
  "Georgian colleagues displayed a particular interest in 
Russian enterprises of the fuel-and-energy sector," Soskovets 
said. He pointed out that a number of Russian joint stock 
societies expressed the readiness to take part in the 
modernisation of oil processing complexes on the territory of 
Georgia. However, Soskovets emphasised that "our relations 
should develop on the basis of parity and mutual advantage". 
  Soskovets did not rule out a possibility of granting a 
credit 
to Georgia worth 20 billion roubles in the near future. He 
pointed out that the Russian side seeks to connect these funds 
with the so-called tied credit. 
  Speaking about the economic situation in Russia, Soskovets, 
who is in charge of issues of the fuel and energy sector, the 
military-industrial complex and industry in general, said that 
the state budget remains one of the most pressing problems 
today. He pointed out that at present, the Russian Government, 
on the one hand, has been holding consultations with ministries 
and state committees on the development of the coordinated 
system of mutual payments between enterprises, and on the other 
hand, seeks to conduct a tough policy of allocating credits to 
different branches of the economy. 

</TEXT>

