<F P=100> Georgia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Abkhazia Claims `Complete Control' of Gali Region </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0702124894 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1143 GMT 7 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0702124894 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] The situation in Abkhazia's Gali region, where 
fighting continued last Saturday [5 February] between Abkhazian 
and Georgian formations, "is under Abkhazia's complete control," 
Deputy Prime Minister of the Abkhazian Government Vladimir 
Mikanba told Interfax on Monday. 
  He announced that on February 7, the Abkhazian army 
continued 
to eliminate Georgia's bandit formations. Some of them have 
been pressed into the mountains, while others have been 
encircled or taken prisoner. Georgia has lost about 60 men near 
the village of Okumi. 
  Mikanba alleged that there had been about 1,500 Georgian 
militants in the Gali Region, who had been given the order to 
seize the Gali region and the city of Ochamchira. 
  He also announced that the Georgian formations located on 
the 
left "Georgian" bank of the Inguri River opened artillery fire 
to support their units stationed in Abkhazia. Abkhazian forces 
did not open fire at the left bank, he said. 
  He denied the reports by the Georgian media about the 
execution of Georgian civilians in the Gali region's village of 
Bagdadi. 
  According to sources in Sukhumi, since September 30, 1993, 
when the Georgian troops had to leave Abkhazia, combat 
operations in its territory have not been as fierce as they are 
now. Abkhazians are using tanks and artillery. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

