<F P=100> Georgia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Most Georgians Support Russian-Georgian Treaty </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0402203994 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1752 GMT 4 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0402203994 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Most Georgians support concluding the 
Russian-Georgian treaty on friendship, cooperation and 
good-neighborly relations signed by Russian President Boris 
Yeltsin and Georgian leader Eduard Shevardnadze in Tbilisi 
yesterday. 
  According to an opinion poll conducted by the sociological 
service of the Georgian agency BS-Press, a total of 91% of 
respondents support signing the treaty, while only 4% 
said they 
do not. Five percent of those asked abstained from answering 
the question. 
  A total of 73.4% of Georgians believe that the 
treaty will 
play an important part in the settlement of the armed conflict 
in Abkhazia, while 11.9% were skeptical about that and 
another 
14.7% found it difficult to answer. 
  As many as 59% of those asked believe that deploying 
Russian 
troops in Georgia on Russian conditions (3 military bases in the 
republic) is in Georgia's interests, while 19.2% are 
categorically against the deployment. Another 21.8% said 
they 
were too incompetent in such issues to provide any answer. 
  During the poll, 10 out of 500 said this was the first that 
they had heard that Yeltsin had visited Georgia. 

</TEXT>

