<F P=100> Georgia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Shevardnadze Calls Yeltsin's Visit `Historic' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0402184894 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1752 GMT 4 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0402184894 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Georgian leader Eduard Shevardnadze has described as 
historic the visit to Tbilisi February 3 by Russian President 
Yeltsin. 
  Addressing in Tbilisi Friday the conference of the Union of 
Georgian Citizens, he said that the signed agreements would 
provide results shortly. 
  Shevardnadze called groundless the fears by certain forces 
in 
Russia and Georgia that the treaty of friendship and cooperation 
between the two countries may destabilize the situation in the 
North Caucasus. The Georgian leader said that the treaty had 
been signed for a ten year period, and if one of the sides did 
not demand its annulment, it would be extended automatically. 
  Speaking about the possible creation in Georgia of Russian 
military bases, Shevardnadze said that the problem was not yet 
solved. At the talks, he said, the two sides only agreed on 
forming expert teams to consider the problem. 
  Answering the question on circumstances behind the death 
Thursday in Tbilisi of deputy Georgian Defense Minister Niko 
Kekelidze, the Georgian leader said that the act of terrorism 
(Kekelidze died following an explosion in his house) was not 
committed for political reasons. Organized crime is behind the 
murder. 
  Speaking about the resignation of Georgian Defense Minister 
Georgiy Karkarashvili, Shevardnadze said that he would meet him 
and ask him to explain the reasons. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

