<F P=100> Georgia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Public Polled on Results of Yeltsin Visit </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0602132594 Moscow Russian Television Network in Russian 
1100 GMT 6 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0602132594 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow Russian Television Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By correspondent M. Vardzelashvili from Tbilisi] </F>
  [Text] The reaction in political circles and among the 
population in Georgia to Boris Yeltsin's visit to the republic 
is not unequivocal. However, most politicians and inhabitants 
of Georgia assess positively the signing of the bilateral treaty 
with Russia. 
  The Department for Sociological Studies at the Georgian 
Academy of Sciences and also leading republic's newspapers have 
published the results of the sociological poll of the population 
following the Russian president's visit to Georgia. 
  According to the poll results, 67 percent of respondents 
assess positively the normalization of Russian-Georgian 
relations; 10 percent of those polled view the visit by the 
Russian delegation negatively. As for the rest, they find it 
difficult to define their position. 
  At the same time, 90 percent of respondents believe the 
establishment of good-neighborly relations with Russia is in 
Georgia's state interests. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

