<F P=100> UKRAINE </F>
<F P=101> International Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Holds News Conference </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0402183294 Kiev UNIAR in Ukrainian 1524 GMT 4 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0402183294 </F>
<F P=104>  Kiev UNIAR </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Ukrainian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Kiev, 4 Feb -- Ukraine's Foreign Affairs Minister 
Anatoliy Zlenko spoke at a news conference in the Foreign 
Affairs Ministry on the attitude of the world community to the 
trilateral agreement on nuclear disarmament signed in Moscow. 
This attitude, he said, was absolutely positive, showing the 
world community's appreciation of the historic step taken by 
Ukraine. The minister noted that the resolution adopted by the 
Supreme Council of Ukraine yesterday [3 February] was especially 
significant, in that the Supreme Council appreciated the steps 
made by the president and the government to follow the Supreme 
Council's recommendations contained in the 18 November 1993 
resolution. 
  "It is worth stressing," Anatoliy Zlenko said, "that the 
Supreme Council, having withdrawn its reservations on Article 5 
of the Lisbon Protocol, thus confirmed Ukraine's intention to 
join the Nuclear Nonproliferation Treaty [NPT] as soon as 
possible, as a state that does not possess nuclear arms. This 
way, failure to make a decision on joining the NPT should not be 
regarded as the Supreme Council's negative stand on the treaty, 
but only as the Supreme Council's intention to examine this 
issue at a separate Supreme Council session." 
  The minister then said that the Supreme Council's decision 
clears the way for exchanging instruments of ratification and 
thus completing the process of the ratification of the START 
Treaty. 
  Anatoliy Zlenko told journalists that bilateral and 
trilateral talks between experts will be held in the near future 
with regard to the practical implementation of the principles 
laid down in the trilateral statement and its appendix signed on 
14 January in Moscow. In the minister's view, the Supreme 
Council's decision makes it possible to speed up talks with 
international financial organizations, the European Union, and 
the leading Western states on the granting of effective aid to 
Ukraine for its economic reform. 
  In reply to journalists' questions, the foreign minister 
said 
that only three nuclear warheads had been transferred from 
Ukraine to Russia so far, due to their unsatisfactory technical 
condition. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

